<HEADLINE> SIB's Proposals to Safeguard Compensation Arrangements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 15 (Xinhua) - The Securities and Investment
Board (SIB) today published a Consultative Paper on proposals to
change the Investors Compensation Scheme (ICS) 100 million pounds
(160 million US dollars) annual compensation limit.
</P>
<P>
This change will enable investors to receive compensation in
the event that claims exceed the current annual limit.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Winckler, the SIB's Chief Executive, said: "The current
proposals are being made as a precautionary measure in the
interests of investor protection."
</P>
<P>
The proposals seek to remove a risk that the current method of
applying the annual limit could exclude investors from
compensation otherwise due to them.
</P>
<P>
The proposals also aim to raise the amount of the limit from
100 million pounds to 200 million pounds (320 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Investors Compensation Scheme limited is the management
company established to operate the Financial Services
(Compensation of Investors) Rules which are made by the SIB under
the Financial Services Act 1986.
</P>
<P>
The Scheme enables investors to claim compensation of up to
48,000 pounds (76,800 US dollars) for loss of money or investments
due to the negligence or fraud of failed UK investment companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
