<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, October 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- American Professor Steven Chu, French Professor
Claude Cohen-Tannoudji and American scientist William D. Philips
have won the 1997 Nobel Physics Prize "for development of methods
to cool and trap atoms with laser light," the Royal Swedish
Academy of Sciences announced today.
</P>
<P>
The new methods of investigation developed by the Nobel
Laureates "have contributed greatly to increasing our knowledge of
the interplay between radiation and matter," the Academy said.
(Sweden-Nobel Prize-Physics)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of China's Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), arrived here today for a
three-day visit to Japan.
</P>
<P>
This is Tung's first visit to the country as HKSAR chief
executive following China's resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1 this year. (Tung-Japan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen said
today his government's most important task is to stabilize the
political situation in order to secure a smooth election next year.
</P>
<P>
He told the inauguration ceremony for a military building that
the National Assembly and his government are speeding up
preparations for the general election scheduled for May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The government has to concentrate on three major tasks, he
said. In addition to stabilizing the political situation, it had
to solve economic issues and establish and perfect a legal
system. (Cambodia-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The Japanese government will begin talks with the
three ruling parties on establishing liaison offices with the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), Kyodo news service
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its two
non-cabinet allies -- the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New
Party Sakigake, asked the government to set up a formal channel
between Japan and the DPRK to discuss bilateral issues.
(Japan-DPRK-Liaison Office)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Troops coming from the Angolan enclave Cabinda invaded
Pointe-Noire, the "oil capital" of the Congo Republic, this
morning and met little resistance from the government troops loyal
to President Pascal Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Democratic and Popular Forces (DPF) loyal to
former President Denis Sassou Nguesso said hours later in
Libreville, capital of Gabon, that the DPF forces had taken
Pointe-Noire. (Congo-Oil-City Fall) 
</P>
