<HEADLINE> US Retail Sales Continue to Increase in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Retail sales rose by
0.3 percent in September, the fourth consecutive increase, U.S.
Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that retail sales increased to a seasonally
adjusted 215.5 billion dollars last month following stronger gains
in June, July and August.
</P>
<P>
Receipts at U.S. department stores and other general
merchandisers fell by 0.6 percent, while sales dropped 0.7 percent
at clothing and accessory shops. Both were the sharpest declines
in five months.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales last month rose 0.6 percent, the fourth consecutive
advance but not nearly as strong as increases in the previous
three months. Furniture dealers also reported a 0.6 percent
increase in September, the sixth month without a decline.
</P>
<P>
The report didn't contradict analysts' belief that U.S.
economic growth is moderating. They say that the question is
whether the moderation is enough to persuade the U.S. Federal
Reserve to refrain from raising short-term interest rates to cool
growth and squelch any incipient inflation pressures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
