<HEADLINE> Roundup: East Asia Economic Summit Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- After three days of heated
work and discussions, the World Economic Forum's Sixth East Asia
Economic Summit closed its doors in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center (HKCEC) tonight, with a number of notable
results.
</P>
<P>
Leaving the HKCEC building, many of the 1,000 delegates from
over 50 countries described the meeting as successful and
beneficial not only to the economic growth in East Asia but also
to global economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China's economic development and prospects was one of the three
topics at the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the plenary session of the summit, Chairman of
China's
State Economic and Trade Commission Wang Zhongyu noted that China
had made great progress in its economic development since 1979,
under the policy of reform and opening to the outside world
initiated by the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Its annual growth rate of gross domestic product (GDP) reached
12.1 percent in the 1991-1996 period, he said, adding that its
economy will grow at an annual rate of 8 percent in the remaining
years of the current century, while the country's annual inflation
rate will be kept below 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
China could maintain a 7 percent growth rate in the first 10
years of
the next century, he said, predicting that "a more open and
prosperous
China will become an important participant in the world economy,
particularly in the East Asian economy, and a cooperation partner
to be
trusted."
</P>
<P>
Most of the participants shared the view that China had
embarked on a track of continuous, rapid and healthy economic
development and would become a more open and prosperous country
and play a more important role in global economic growth in the
coming century.
</P>
<P>
As to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China,
many delegates including Philippine President Fidel Ramos said
everything has been good in the region since it returned to the
motherland on July 1. The fact that Hong Kong was chosen as the
summit's venue indicates that the world says OK to its situation
after its return, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The economic situation and prospects in the Southeast Asian
countries and the East Asian region as a whole was another topic
of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told the meeting that he expected the Southeast Asian
countries to resume its high growth after the recent currency
turmoil, noting that their economic fundamentals remain strong.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to "turn this financial crisis into a
possibility," although the next year or two will be difficult for
some
countries in the Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Prime Minister of Singapore Goh Chok Tong also
expressed his optimism about the Southeast Asian economies, saying
countries affected by the recent financial turbulence in the
region will be able to recover fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
The recent financial turmoil represents only a temporary,
though painful, setback to the onward march of Southeast Asian
economies, he said, voicing his faith that while near-term growth
in East Asia will
likely slow down, the economies in the region will not stall
because of
good economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in foreign direct investment in the region will
continue," he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, a number of influential bankers present at the meeting
pointed out that the recent financial crisis had not broken out
overnight, and instead it was an inescapable result of
accumulation of economic strains after years of high growth.
</P>
<P>
The crisis will bring about an adjustment policy to be
implemented for
at least a year, they said, predicting that the regional economy
will
return to the fast growth track in the second half of 1999 as a
result of
good economic fundamentals and a long tradition of high savings
rate.
</P>
<P>
The world will enter into the next millennium with the bulk of
East Asia seeing better and stronger growth, they said.
</P>
<P>
The third major topic for discussion was whether or not it is
necessary to build networks for growth among East Asia, West
Europe and North America in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"The three regions together generate almost 80 percent of
global GNP
(gross national product) and some 70 percent of world trade. There
are
strong synergetic possibilities in their leading industries," the
Philippine president said.
</P>
<P>
But some speakers pointed out the need to do things step by
step, urging every country to both seek for a broad international
cooperation and stand on its own feet.
</P>
<P>
In his concluding remarks, Managing Director of the World
Economic Forum Claude Smadja emphasized that the Geneva-based
organization will make further efforts to stimulate the economic
growth in East Asia and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the forum had decided to hold its 7th East
Asia Economic Summit in Singapore on October 19 next year, and had
planned an East Asia-Pacific Economic Summit in Australia in the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
