<HEADLINE> McAleese Remains Favorite to Win Irish Presidency Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Mary McAleese remains the
favorite candidate to win the Irish presidential election due to
be held on October 30, according to an opinion poll showed on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,000 Irish voters, conducted by the MRBI
research company, revealed that McAleese, the candidate of the
ruling Fianna Fail party, remained ahead of the other four
contenders by commanding a "first preference" vote of 32 percent
under the country's proportional representation system.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Fine Gael party candidate Mary Banotti,
grand-niece of the country's founding father Michael Collins,
snatched a 24-percent support, according to press reports from
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
However, the poll also showed a slip in support for the Labour
Party's anti-nuclear campaigner Adi Roche, who received just 13
percent support in the poll, down from 22 percent two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Roche, who heads a charity to help children from the region
devastated by the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear disaster, saw her
favorable position losing after some of her former employees
accused her of a ruthless management style.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the only male candidate Derek Nally and well-known
singer Dana, whose real name is Rosemary Scallon, enjoyed a
seven-percent support respectively. The survey also indicated that
some 17 percent voters remained undecided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
