<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Approves New Package for Offshore Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
approved today a new incentive package to activate the petroleum
exploration in the country's offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
Proposed by the Ministry of Petroleum and Natural Resources,
the package includes low tax rate of 40 percent compared with the
existing tax capped at 50 percent under the concession system and
accelerated depreciation for capital facilities, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, the government will not share any rise in
the exploration or development.
</P>
<P>
But it will capture the revenues through profit oil/profit gas
on a slicing scale after recovery of cost which has an upper limit
of 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
The package also includes payment or rentals, production bonus,
marine research fee as well as training obligations, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
They said the package would be applicable for five years and
would come into force immediately after making necessary changes
in the relevant laws.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that the new package will attract private
investment in petroleum exploration in the offshore area, where
no drilling activity has been undertaken for seven years.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the volume of sediments in offshore
Pakistan is huge and the existing information indicates the
presence of numerous structures which could contain major oil and
gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
The proposed package will enable the petroleum industry to
re-evaluate the possibilities for offshore exploration, said the
sources, adding that a major oil and gas discovery in the offshore
area will have a significant impact on the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
