<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Government Faces Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A confidence vote for the revived
Prodi Government will be taken tomorrow, Italian Lower House
Speaker Luciano Violante announced today after Prodi made his
opening speech in the confidence debate.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Romano Prodi stressed the role of collective
bargaining in enacting both pension reforms and the key move to a
35-hour work week by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that work-week reductions will be applied
variably in different regions, taking into account economic
discrepancies between the North and the South.
</P>
<P>
The confidence crisis erupted when the government presented the
1998 budget to the parliament, with the aim of helping Italy to
become one of the charter members to the European economic and
monetary union.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Refoundation party, holding the balance of power
in the lower house of parliament, complained that the budget had
too many deep cuts in social and welfare spending, and few
measures to stimulate employment. It vowed to back away from it.
</P>
<P>
As a comprise with the Communist Refoundation, the government
said yesterday that industrial workers will be shielded from cuts
in seniority pensions (those taken after 35 years' work regardless
of age).
</P>
<P>
The move put the Prodi government back into Parliament with a
newly compact majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
