<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Sets Date for Final Land Acquisition for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean president Robert
Mugabe today said the Zimbabwe government will finalise acquiring
land for the resettlement exercise next year, adding that people
should be offered land before the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the midlands provincial leadership, Mugabe said
commercial farmers who have more than one farm would have one of
their farms designated for resettlement purposes.
</P>
<P>
He added the Zimbabwe government would not go back to the
negotiating table with Britain to discuss about the land issue
since the U.K. had indicated during the Lancaster house talks
that it would compensate farmers whose farms would be acquired.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the government would never pay compensation
to farmers who would lose their land as this was the
responsibility of the British government which colonised
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe had sent a delegation to the U.K. stating its
position that if funds were not forthcoming the government would
acquire land without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
National land acquisition committee chairman Joseph Msika said
five million hectares were targetted for acquisition.
</P>
<P>
He said the target was to identify underutilised and derelict
land, and farms owned by absentee landlords.
</P>
<P>
At least 62,000 people have been resettled since independence
but another 100,000 still wait for the land which the government
has been promising for the past 17 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0015 </DOCNO>
