<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Lowest Jobless Figures for 17 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 15 (Xinhua) - September's unemployment figures
in Britain showed a fall of 27,800 to 1,467,600, at an annual rate
of 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest figure for 17 years, according to official
figures released here today.
</P>
<P>
It also was the 19th consecutive monthly fall in the jobless
total although economists had been predicting a steeper drop.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment in Britain, as measured by the official
statistics, is running at under half the European average of
10.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Britain compares favorable with the rest of Europe with an ILO
unemployment rate of under 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, one economist said, while unemployment in
Britain is falling, it is still on an upward trend in Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, the release of the figures coincided with a report
from the Bank of England warning of the possibility of rapidly
rising wage costs in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Philip Shaw, analyst of Investec said: "The pace of decline in
the claimant count measure of unemployment has eased back somewhat
and earnings growth has remained steady.... "
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless it is unlikely to ease the Bank of England's
concerns over the potentially inflationary implications of the
tightness of the labor market," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Govt Announces Safeguards to Counter Adverse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
today announced substantial safeguards to protect common men from
the adverse impact of rupee adjustment against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The State Bank of Pakistan today adjusted the dollar-rupee
(buying) rate by 8.71 percent from 40.52 rupees to a dollar to
44.05 rupees.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz
said that "realignment" of exchange rate will improve exports and
competitive position of local industry which is facing adverse
conditions in the international market.
</P>
<P>
He said the resultant increase in petroleum prices following
the exchange rate adjustment is not being passed onto items like
kerosene, high speed diesel, light diesel oil and furnace oil.
</P>
<P>
"As a result there should be no increase in bus fare, transport
charges or tractor hire charges," he said, adding that similarly
stable prices of furnace oil will ensure more stable electricity
prices.
</P>
<P>
However the prices of motor spirit, super and high octane have
recorded increases ranging from 50 to 61 paisas per liter.
</P>
<P>
There will be no increase in the release price of wheat, even
though the price of imported wheat goes up, said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The minister also brushed aside any increase in the budgeted
cost of debt servicing, saying "We are now borrowing from the
local market at the lower rate and partly due to more revenues
from enhanced customs duties."
</P>
<P>
To subside the impact of adjustment on the agricultural sector,
the minister announced that there will be no upward revision in
the prices of fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
In overall terms, the exchange rate adjustment will have
positive impact on the agricultural sector. Cotton growers will
receive higher prices for cotton in rupees, sugar surplus will
become exportable at more competitive prices and rice exports will
be stimulated, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the most important impact of realignment of exchange
rate will be on manufactured exports, particularly high value
textile and non-traditional exports, said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said the exchange rate adjustment is necessitated by
external or internal factors and in case of Pakistan both have
been unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the external factor, he said the Pakistani currency
is linked to the U.S. dollar and the dollar has gained
considerable strength in terms of other currencies.
</P>
<P>
He termed the currency upheaval in Southeast Asia since July as
another external factor of some urgency for making adjustment in
rupee value.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the currency crisis in Southeast Asia, the Thai
baht has been devalued by 30 percent against the U.S. dollar and
the Malaysian ringgit and the Indonesia rupiah by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister observed that since many of Pakistan's exports
like textile and rice compete with these countries, "our
competitive advantage had been further eroded."
</P>
<P>
"Because of these two external factors, the need for an
exchange rate adjustment was in any case necessary but its
compulsion was further accentuated by internal factor - inflation,
a rate of inflation that is higher than that in our main trading
partners," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the nine month period from October 1996 to June 1997, he
said, the rate of inflation in Pakistan was 8.35 percent, while
the annual rate of inflation now stands at 11.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
He noted that inflation rates of Pakistan's major trading
partners like South Korea, Japan, the U.S., Germany and China are
much lower. That is also the major reason for today's exchange
rate readjustment.
</P>
<P>
To a question about the impact of rupee adjustment on the
defense budget, Aziz said, "It will have no impact on it as the
adjustment is less than the cushion available in the budget".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0018 </DOCNO>
