<HEADLINE> Southeast European Parliament Summit Opens in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting of the
presidents of Parliament from the countries of southeastern Europe
opened here today with the aim of exploring possibilities for
further cooperation between the legislatures in the region.
</P>
<P>
The first top-level meeting of the parliaments of the region is
being attended by the Parliament Presidents of Albania, Bosnia,
Bulgaria, Yugoslavia, the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia
(FYROM), Romania, Croatia and Slovenia, with observers from the
parliamentary assemblies of international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, Greek Parliament President Apostolos
Kaklamanis said that cooperation should be strengthened on a more
permanent basis within the framework of a "parliamentary advisory
assembly," the first aim of which would be to organize meetings of
house presidents on a regular, rotating basis along the lines of
similar meetings in the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Parliament Speaker Milomir Milic proposed Belgrade as
the venue for the first meeting of the parliamentary advisory
assembly of the southeastern countries in Europe in June next
year.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Parliament President Petre Roman hoped that the image
of southeastern Europe could be enhanced through greater contact
between the parliaments of the region.
</P>
<P>
Moldovan Parliament President Timitru Motpan stressed that
weight should be placed on efforts to combat arms smuggling and
narcotics trafficking, while specific initiatives should be
undertaken against terrorism and national isolationism.
</P>
<P>
He added that cooperation should also be advanced on ecological
matters and the protection of the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
