<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Accused of Ill-Treating Kaunda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The United National
Independence Party (UNIP), Zambia's main opposition party, today
accused the government of ill-treating former President Kenneth
Kaunda and threatened to take the government to court.
</P>
<P>
At a regular news briefing held here at the UNIP headquarters
in the capital, Bwendo Mwengela, publicity and information
secretary, told reporters that as early as in March 1994, the
government has decided to give Kaunda a choice "to allow
government either to build him a house or buy a house for him"
and provide him with three vehicles, three drivers as well as
several servants and a secretary.
</P>
<P>
However, the government refused to pay a total of 500,000 U.S
Dollars' rent arrears that Kaunda owes his landlord and failed to
provide vehicles, according to Mwengela.
</P>
<P>
He threatened to take the Multi-Party Movement for Democracy
(MMD) government to court because of its "lukewarm attitude"
towards the housing and transport of Kaunda, president of UNIP
and the first president who led the country to independence from
Britain in 1964 and ruled Zambia until 1991 when MMD came into
power.
</P>
<P>
"The party and Kaunda is now left with no choice but to take
the MMD government to court," said Mwengela in a front-page story
in Times of Zambia published today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the government will not pay rent arrears for
the house Kaunda rents from a businessman since the act provides
for provision of a house by way of buying or building one instead
of paying house rent for a former president.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Richard Sakala, President Frederick Chiluba's press
aide as saying that there is no such a provision in Kaunda's
retirement benefits act and the government is not responsible
for paying the rent.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between UNIP and the government over housing of
Kaunda came up recently after the former president's landlord
threatened to evict him from his house if the rent which has
accrued from July 1993 is not paid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
