<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Chair U.N. Human Rights Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa was Tuesday
endorsed by the African countries to chair the 1998 United
Nations Commission on Human Rights (UNCHR) in Geneva, the Foreign
Affairs Ministry announced today.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, endorsed for a three-year term from 1997, was
the only candidate. It is Africa's turn to chair the commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission, one of the bodies established by the U.N.
economic and social council, is responsible for preparing
recommendations and reports on matters such as international
conventions on civil liberties, the status of women, protection
of minorities, prevention of discrimination and human rights
situations in various countries.
</P>
<P>
South African Ambassador to Geneva Jackie Selebi who is also
the permanent representative to the U.N., would chair the UNCHR
session, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
