<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Party Adopts 1998 Election Platform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LEIPZIG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Under the mottos of "jobs for
all", and "zero tolerance to crime", German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) today set out a party
agenda with which it will start the campaign for general elections
scheduled for September next year.
</P>
<P>
Under a party platform adopted before the end of its three-day
congress in the eastern German city of Leipzig, the CDU called for
liberalization and structural reforms in the German economy in
order to cure the country's main malaise at present -- a
record-high jobless total of about 4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
More part-time jobs, flexible working hours, more temporary
jobs and modest wage increases were among the main remedies
proposed by the CDU.
</P>
<P>
A cut of work week to 32 hours, as suggested by the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) and trade unions, has
been firmly rejected by Kohl's party.
</P>
<P>
Describing anti-crime battle as another top policy priority,
the CDU pledged tougher measures to crack down on the country's
increasing offenses.
</P>
<P>
"With 6.7 million criminal offenses, over two million criminal
suspects and a crime clear-up rate of only 49 percent in 1996, the
interior security of Germany is under threat everyday," the CDU
anti-crime paper said.
</P>
<P>
The CDU today also pledged reforms to improve the country's
education system. On the European issues, it vowed to hold on to
the target of a punctual start of the single European currency and
called for stronger coordination in Europe to combat organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
Besides adopting the party agenda, the three-day CDU congress
also confirmed Kohl as its chancellor candidate for the next
general elections scheduled on September 27, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
