<HEADLINE> Angolan Peace Process Comes to An End, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Joao Lourenco, senior official
of the People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola, said here
today that the Angolan Peace Process has now nearly come to an
end, with peace almost becoming a reality.
</P>
<P>
Lourenco made the statement in a speech at the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
According to him, although the peace process is slow in its
progress, it nearly comes to an end. The Angolan people have
enjoyed rights to peace, which is a fact irreversible to
politicians' wishes.
</P>
<P>
Lourenco believed that the two signatories of the Lusaka Peace
Accord have participated in the peace process and made their
contributions to peace, although the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) got engaged in the process under
pressures from the international community.
</P>
<P>
The No. 1127 resolution passed recently by the United Nations
Security Council rules that it will impose sanctions on UNITA if
the former rebel movement fails to accomplish the tasks
stipulated in the peace agreement within the prescribed deadline.
</P>
<P>
It's only 15 days before the UN deadline, but there are still
certain tasks unfinished by UNITA, said Lourenco, who urged UNITA
leaders to make efforts for the realization of final peace.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the drafting of new constitution for Angola,
Lourenco noted, a modern constitution should reflect the
historical, political and economic situations in the country so
as to adapt to challenges facing the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Decides to Postpone No-Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma decided
today to postpone the vote of no-confidence in the Russian
government until next Wednesday, according to the Itar-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma made the decision following an appeal of the
president Boris Yeltsin to drop the no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
During today's debates on the vote at the plenary session of
the State Duma Speaker of the Duma Gennady Seleznyov contacted
twice through telephone with the president.
</P>
<P>
According to Seleznyov, Yeltsin called on the deputies not to
carry the issue through to the resignation of the government
today. The president said "I don't want confrontation, I don't
want new early elections."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also showed readiness to start the work of a 'round
table' with the participation of political parties and movements
on the most important issues.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to postpone the voting was put forward by Russian
Communists' leader Gennady Zyuganov and backed by the Agrarian and
Power To People factions in the lower house of the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The decisive backing came from leader of the ultranationalist
Liberal Democratic Party of Russia (LDPR) Vladimir zhirinovsky who
is firmly in command of 51 voted of his faction, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of both pro-governmental Our Home Is Russia faction and
liberal Yabloko Alexander Shokhin and Grigory Yavlinsky insisted
on voting the no-confidence motion today, but slight majority of
deputies, 228 deputies, voted for the postponement of the
non-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin today also urged the
State Duma to drop its no-confidence vote, saying that "We need to
work on the main documents today. I accept any criticism."
</P>
<P>
According to the premier, the last week of "tough talk" between
the government and the Duma, the federal budget lost over 500
million US dollars and oil and gas companies even more.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin admitted that the draft tax code really needs
correction, and agreed that the number of taxes should be reduced.
He said the president hopes that common sense and responsibility
will prevail in the Duma, adding the executive branch is open to
cooperation with legislators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
