<HEADLINE> Russian FM to Visit Egypt on Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov will start his three-day visit to Egypt on October 29 as
part of his six-leg Mideast tour to push forward the peace
process, Russian Ambassador to Egypt Vladimir Gudev said today.
</P>
<P>
The visit was agreed upon during the talks between Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin
in Moscow in September, he said, quoted by the Middle East News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will be the last leg of the Russian foreign minister's
trip in the region which will take him to Lebanon, Syria, Israel,
Jordan and the Palestinian self-rule areas starting from October
24.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is expected to carry with him fresh ideas on
activating the deadlocked Middle East peace process, Gudev added.
</P>
<P>
Russia has mainly been absent from the Middle East arena over
the past few years, leaving the United States as the sole broker
whose role was often criticized by many Arabs as leaning toward
Israel.
</P>
<P>
It was Mubarak who in his recent visit to Moscow asked Yeltsin
to revive Russia's role as one of the co-sponsors of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
As to whether Russia will attend the mid-November Arab-Israeli
economic conference in Doha, Qatar, Gudev said that Moscow has
received an invitation in the capacity as one of the co-sponsors
of the peace march that started in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said he believes there are no obstacles
hindering Russia's participation in the conference with the aim of
improving Arab-Israeli ties.
</P>
<P>
"Strenuous efforts should be exerted to allow both sides to
reach tangible results regarding the peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
This process came to a halt since Israel began construction of
a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in March. The Doha
conference, controversially symbolic of an Arab-Israeli rapport,
has been opposed by a number of Arab countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
