<HEADLINE> Swaziland's Strike Enters Third Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A strike of more than
40,000 wokers in Swaziland entered its third day today, with no
solution in sight, reports reaching here from Mbabane said.
</P>
<P>
The industrial action, which began on Monday, is over a wide
range demands,including wage rises and constitutional changes in
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported on Tuesday that the strike's
organiser,the Swaziland Federation of Trade Unions, might call
off the action in view of growing signs that workers were
ambivalent about the strike.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's major foreign exchange earner,sugar,is among the
worst affected sectors of the economy by the current labour
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The sugar industry was paralysed in February when employees
laid down thier tools over improved working conditions.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland is the only country in southern Africa which has not
introduced political reforms.
</P>
<P>
But memebers of a constitutional review commission are visiting the
kingdom to get people's views on whether they want a new system or
remain under a traditional monarchy. 
</P>
