<HEADLINE> GCC Joint Naval Exercises End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states ended today their annual joint naval
maneuvers which began on October 4, the Bahraini news agency
monitored here reported.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day exercises, codenamed "Solidarity-5", were aimed at
strengthening military cooperation among the GCC members, which
include Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Bahrain,
Qatar and Oman, GCC military officials said.
</P>
<P>
The maneuvers which took place off the coast of Bahrain came
days after Iran bombed two Iranian rebel bases inside southern
Iraq, causing tensions in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has accused Iran of violating the "no-fly zone" over
southern Iraq and warned against further violations. The
U.S. aircraft carrier Nimitz, which arrived in the Gulf Sunday
and armed with 75 warplanes and six other warships, has been
deployed in northern Gulf waters.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., Britain and France imposed a "no-fly" ban in
southern Iraq after the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
A day before the arrival of the Nimitz, the Iranian navy also
launched military exercises along its coasts. More than 50
warships, including two Russia-made submarines, and scores of
planes and helicopters took part in the 10-day war games, which
covered 24,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Iran strongly opposes the U.S. military presense in the Gulf
region, where some 20,000 U.S. troops and 29 warships are
deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
