<HEADLINE> Angola Can't Meet Demand for Food: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Agriculture
Carlos Fernandes said today that despite its great potentials in
agriculture, fishery and mineral industries, Angola is still
incapable of meeting the people's needs for food at present.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here at a press conference to mark
tomorrow's World Food Day.
</P>
<P>
According to him, statistics from the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization show that 45 percent of Angolans are
mal-nutritioned, and the per capita consumption of food is merely
1,740 calorie, which fail to reach the health standard.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the situation to two-decade long
civil war, which brought about severe social and economic
damages.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, Angola should take up incentive
measures to promote public and private investments and personnel
training, so as to achieve sustainable development in
agriculture, forestry and the whole rural areas to meet people's
needs for food.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes also announced October 15 will be observed as Rural
Women's Day in Angola to encourage women, who have been a vital
force for the country's agriculture, to make further contributions
to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
