<HEADLINE> Israeli FM to Visit Jordan to Remedy Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy is to visit Jordan next month as part of Israeli
government's damage-control efforts to remedy the strained ties
with Amman.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Radio reported today that Levy's visit was announced
after Amman expressed satisfaction with the recent actions taken
by Israel to restore friendly relationship with Jordan damaged
by the failed attempt of Israeli secret service Mossad to
assassinate a Hamas leader Khaled Mashaal last month.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Ambassador to Israel Omar Rafai met with Israeli
Foreign Ministry's Director-General Eitan Ben-Tsur Tuesday to
discuss ways to get the bilateral ties back on track.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was reported to be pleased with Levy for his
handling of the Mashaal affair. This was evident in Rafai's
statement that Jordan wanted to work closely with Israeli
Foreign Ministry to advance the peace.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was angered by the Mossad operation in its capital,
denouncing Israel for infringing of its sovereignty and
territorial integrity. Under the Jordanian presure, Israel was
forced to release jailed Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin early
October, who returned to his home in Gaza, and 70 other
Jordanian and Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Israel is especially concerned about the suspension of security
cooperation with Jordan, which provided crucial intelligence
information on some of Israel's Arab enemies. Jordan has demanded
Israeli embassy in Amman to reduce the number of security
personnels following the Mashaal affair.
</P>
<P>
To allay Jordanian anger over the lack of economic benefits
from the 1994 peace treaty, Israeli government has ordered the
acceleration of negotiations on constructing a joint international
airport in Jordan's Red Sea resort city Aqaba in order to
promote tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
