<HEADLINE> Palestinians Accuse Israel of Stalling in Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian permanent
representative to the Arab League (AL) said today Israel has been
stalling in its current talks with the Palestinian side, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sobeih today delivered a message from Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to AL's Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid
on the latest developments in the Mideast peace process and the
ongoing Palestinian-Israeli negotiations as well as other Arab
issues.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli side so far made no positive step and only speaks
about issues that have nothing to do with the essence of the peace
process," Sobeih complained following his meeting with Abdel
Meguid.
</P>
<P>
Israeli intransigent practices do not contribute to pushing
forward the peace process, he said, adding that the aim of
stalling is to serve the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Eight Palestinian-Israeli committees resumed talks two weeks
ago on implementing interim agreements under which Israel should,
among other things, release Palestinian prisoners and permit the
operation of an airport and a sea port.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian diplomat also voiced dissatisfaction with the
U.S. mediation role, which he said fell short of taking a resolute
stance upon Israel's non-compliance with its peace commitments.
</P>
<P>
"The credibility of the U.S. as a co-sponsor of the peace
process is at stake," he said. "The U.S. ought to bring pressure
to bear on Israel to abide by the agreements signed."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. had reaffirmed the land for peace principle,
implementation of U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and 338
and rejection of unilateral actions and this is why the Arab
countries and Palestinian leadership support the recent American
mediation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of coordination and efforts of the
Arab countries especially inside the U.N. and its Security Council
to restore the Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast Coordinator Dennis Ross will return to the region
this week to follow up the low-level Palestinian-Israeli talks.
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Arafat's deputy Mahmoud
Abbas are scheduled to meet in Washington by the end of this month
to discuss broader issues such as settlements and troop
withdrawal. 
</P>
