<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Expand Petrochemical Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait would expand and
upgrade existing domestic refineries and build new plants to
promote petrochemicals industry, according a Kuwaiti
petrochemicals industries official here today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chairman of Kuwait state-owned Petrochemicals Industries
Company (PIC) Abdel Latif Al-Hadad told a press conference that
the Kuwait Petroleum Corporation (KPC) has put forward a 10-point
ambitious strategy to promote the oil refining industry.
</P>
<P>
He added the strategy involves several projects, including the
founding of a aromatics factory which will cost between 1.5
billion and 1.7 billion U.S. dollars, along with other projects.
</P>
<P>
He also said a two-billion-dollar Equate petrochemical project
which is a joint venture between PIC and Union Carbide Corp. of
the United States would be inaugurated on November 12 and reach
design capacity of 1.45 million tonnes of petrochemicals within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait achieved crude refining capacity of 890,000 barrel per
day in February this year following a program to repair and
upgrade Kuwait's three refineries that were damaged during the
1990-1991 Iraqi occupation.
</P>
<P>
It is now planning to boost domestic refining to 1 million
barrels per day from the figure under a current four-year plan.
</P>
<P>
KPC reported record profits in 1996-97 fiscal year (July 1 to
June 30) of 4.5 billion dollars, the highest figure since the
corporation was founded in 1980, according to a statement issued
by the corporation in September.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is now also improving the export facilities at
the refineries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
