<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Bombards Freetown Telecom Installations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Fighting renewed today between
the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) and the military
junta of Sierra Leone with ECOMOG jet dropping bombs at
telecommunications installations in Freetown, capital of S.Leone.
</P>
<P>
According to the British Broadcasting Corporation, a bomb hit
the installations operating on a hill overlooking the city and
appeared to affect at least the international phone line between
Freetown and Abidjan of Cote d'Voire.
</P>
<P>
Some houses in the surrounding area were also damaged. But no
casualty was reported.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that the bombing is one of a series of
fightings between the two sides since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Last week, ECOMOG bombarded a helicopter gunship and the
military headquarters of the junta, which followed attacks by
the junta on an ECOMOG base in the suburb town of Jui.
</P>
<P>
Fighting was also reported in southeastern Sierra Leone,
especially around Bo, the second largest city of the country.
</P>
<P>
Today's bombing might be a follow-up of fighting in Jui, where
Freetown residents reportedly said heavy gunfire could be heard
through last evening till this morning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state radio was quoted as saying that over 117
Nigerian soldiers had been taken prisoners by this morning.
</P>
<P>
The junta earlier claimed it had captured some 400 Nigerian
soldiers and taken the ECOMOG position in Jui, which was denied
by the multinational peacekeeping force led by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, in a statement today, also denied that it acquired
poisonous gas to counter the aggression of the junta's forces as
aired on the state radio in Freetown on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the allegation as the junta's plot to justify
aggression of ECOMOG, the statement said, "ECOMOG strongly
believes that the junta has acquired poisonous gas which it
probably hope to unleash on the peacekeepers and the thousands of
civilians taking refuge with them in their various locations."
</P>
<P>
"It did so in th case of landmines when it accused ECOMOG but
later began a massive use of the prohibited weapon which
eventually killed several ECOMOG soldiers," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG also accused the junta of holding citizens of other
west African countries in Freetown hostage and using them as
human shield.
</P>
<P>
The fresh exchanges of fire followed a United Nations Security
Council sanctions on Sierra Leone announced last Wednesday aimed
at reinstating the legitimate government led by President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah which was ousted in the coup last May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
