<HEADLINE> Ex-Mayor Sentenced in Turkey for Pro-Islamic Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ankara Security Court today
sentenced a former mayor to four years and seven months in prison
for supporting extremist organizations.
</P>
<P>
The court found Bekir Yildiz, former mayor of an Ankara suburb,
guilty for "aiding armed gangs and provoking hatred and animosity
among people," the Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yildiz, a member of the Islamic Welfare Party, was arrested
for organizing a commemoration of "Al-Quds (Jerusalem) Night" on
February 1 and calling for a state system based on Shariah
(Islamic Law).
</P>
<P>
Then TV reports showing the rally hall was decorated with
pictures of leaders of the radical Islamic groups Hamas and
Hezbollah touched off strong protests from secularists and caused
him his post three days later.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution and laws of Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but
politically secular country, ban anyone from calling for the
implementation of Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
Yildiz also invited then Iranian Ambassador Muhammed Reza
Bagheri to the rally, where the Iranian envoy made a controversial
speech leading to a bitter diplomatic row between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's powerful military, which favors secular rule, has
helped bring the downfall of the previous pro-Islamic
government. Now the pro-secular government under Mesut Yilmaz
government is working hard to arrest the rapidly growing
fundamentalist tendency in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
