<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Welfare Reform Law Sued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Five families, a single man
and a community organization are challenging the constitutionality
of the welfare reform law of Minnesota in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The suit filed in Minneapolis circuit court Wednesday says it
is unconstitutional for the state to deny new residents the same
stipend provided longer-term residents. The reduced grant levels
were designed to keep welfare recipients from moving into the
state.
</P>
<P>
Mid-Minnesota Legal Assistance spokesman Tim Thompson says the
law discriminates against newcomers, United Press International
reported.
</P>
<P>
The law provides that families and individuals applying for Aid
to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) less than 12 months
after moving to Minnesota will receive grants equal only to the
amount paid by the state in which they previously had lived.
</P>
<P>
The standard AFDC grant in Minnesota for a mother and two
children is 532 dollars per month. Thompson said if a family comes
from a state with no AFDC program, that family would receive no
money from Minnesota for a year under the law.
</P>
<P>
The law is similar to one passed in 1991 that applied to the
General Assistance program, which subsequently was struck down.
The Minnesota Supreme Court ruled that the law violated newcomers'
constitutional "right to travel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Sending Team to Congo for Alleged Massacre Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States is sending
a three-person team to the Democratic Republic of Congo in an
attempt to give a push to a stalled U.N. probe into alleged
massacres of Rwandan refugees there, the State Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
"The mission is intended to bridge the differences between the
United Nations and the government of Congo so a human rights team
of the U.N. can conduct a full investigation," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters. "We're trying to see what we
can do to break the impasse."
</P>
<P>
The team includes Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations, Representative Donald Payne and former
Representative Howard Wolpe. Rubin said they were picked for the
team because of "their availability, their familiarity with the
situation and all three met and know (Congo's President Laurent)
Kabila."
</P>
<P>
Rubin repeated previous warnings that if Kabila's Congolese
government failed in cooperation with the probe, the United States
would oppose its acceptance into the "community of nations" and
its access to international financial institutions, and he also
indicated Washington might thus consider supporting the imposition
of sanctions on Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
