<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Fresh Rate Hike Worries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all ended lower today, dragged down by US economic figures which
rekindled inflation worries and by disappointing earnings from
the microchip company Intel.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index on the London market ended down after
stronger-than-expected US sales data sparked fears of a Federal
Reserve rate rise. The index fell by nearly 80 points at one stage
but steadied by the close to end 35.2 points lower at 5,263.7.
</P>
<P>
Cable &AMP; Wireless, HSBC and Standard Chartered were all burdened
by the 2.5 percent slide in Hong Kong while Grand Metropolitan and
Guinness bucked the trend after getting the European Union's
approval of a merger between the two companies.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index closed slightly lower as the
market continued to seek direction, down 8.68 points at 4,193.69.
Dealers said that sectors were mixed with some pressure on
chemical shares.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, share prices also ended lower, with soft
bonds and US interest rate fears putting downward pressure on the
market. The CAC-40 index fell by 13.38 points to close at
2,992.16. 
