<HEADLINE> Netherlands Gives Tanzania $7m Tech-Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands has
committed 45.6 billion shillings (about 7.4 million US Dollars)
in financial and technical support for Tanzania in the next five
years, said a statement from the Royal Netherlands Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The support will go into development programs in five
districts in Kagera Region, four in Shinyanga and one in Arusha,
Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Some 17 billion shillings more have been embarked for various
projects, including women, children and environmental
development, this year.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued in the wake of a three-day working visit
by the Dutch Premier, Wim Kok, further said that an additional
7.5 billion shillings grant would be disbursed to Tanzania for
mixed credit financing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Dutch premier Tuesday reassured Tanzania of his
country's support in social and economic development, calling for
further bilateral ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kok told a press conference in Dar es Salaam that the
Netherlands will strengthen the macro-economic assistance
effective next year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is the largest recipient of Dutch aid in Africa and
the third in the world.
</P>
<P>
Kok and his entourage held talks at the State House with
Tanzanian government officials, touching on a myriad of
socio-economic issues, including long-term plans to ease the
power shortage currently plaguing the country.
</P>
<P>
Kok, who left Dar es Salaam Tuesday for Kagera Region, plans
to visit various development projects funded by the Netherlands
in the region before proceeding to Kigoma Region later for
another tour.
</P>
<P>
He will wind up his three-day working visit Thursday after an
informal meeting with the Netherlands Development Organization
project aimed at supporting small entrepreneurs in Arusha.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
