<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Deficit Falls to 8.9 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's deficit for 1996-97
fell to 8.9 billion dollars (6.4 billion US dollars), Finance
Minister Paul Martin said in Vancouver today.
</P>
<P>
The figure is almost 20 billion dollars down from the previous
fiscal year, and the largest year-over-year improvement in
Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
"This represents the smallest federal government deficit in
over two decades -- indeed, as a proportion of our economy, at 1.1
percent of the gross domestic product, it is the lowest deficit
recorded since 1970-71," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the announcement in releasing the
government's annual Economic and Fiscal Update to the House of
Commons Standing Committee on Finance in Vancouver today.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in the current fiscal year is continuing to decline
and the government is committed to achieve a balanced budget no
later than the next fiscal year, which starts April 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
And it will be the first year that Canada's federal
government's books have been balanced since 1969-70, he said.
</P>
<P>
Martin attributed the deficit decline to several factors,
including the government's restraint measures in the past several
years, a strong economy that generates more revenues.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the falling deficit, Canada's debt-to-GDP ratio
fell to 73.1 percent, the first meaningful decline in some 25
years.
</P>
<P>
Martin ruled out any general tax cuts once the deficit is
eliminated, because it would run the risk of "plunging us back
into deficit, or else forcing crippling cuts to essential
programs."
</P>
<P>
The government said earlier that any surplus would be split
between economic and social needs, and tax cuts and debt
reduction.
</P>
<P>
The 50-50 allocation would be used as a guideline when it is
time to spend any surplus, Martin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
