<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Visit France for Its EU Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz is to fly to Paris Thursday to rally French support for
Ankara's bid for European Union (EU) membership, local newspaper
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz will persuade French President Jacques Chirac to give a
push to Turkey drive in the coming EU summit in December, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been eager for full EU membership, but made little
progress on this track due to its differences with the EU on the
Kurdish issue, its human rights record and weak economy.
</P>
<P>
During the Council of Europe summit in Strasburg, France last
week, Yilmaz held talks with his French counterpart Lionel Jospin
to express Turkey's views over the EU membership issue.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Turkish prime minister flew to Bonn to
seek support from German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
As part of Ankara's efforts for EU membership, Turkish Deputy
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit started his Scandinavian tour Monday
to solicit Swedish and Finnish support for Turkey's bid.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by the European Commission, EU's executive
body, earlier this year excluded Turkey from the ranks of the
prospective candidates for the EU enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper listed Cyprus, a traditional rival of
Turkey, as a candidate, to the great upset of Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had repeatedly criticizing the EU for adopting a
discriminative policy towards it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
