<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European AIDS Conference Ends in Hamburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The sixth European conference on
acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) concluded today in the
northern German port city of Hamburg, urging further efforts in
developing new treatments of the deadly epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,500 AIDS experts from 40 countries attended the five-day
meeting, during which they discussed issues including the kind of
side effects a cocktail of drugs was having on many persons
infected with the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
Drug treatment remains so far the chief method against AIDS.
Conference chairman Professor Manfred Dietrich said that the
achievements were outstanding and treatments proved lasting longer
than were assumed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
However, in treatment, scientists are still uncertain about the
timing and length of a course of combined drugs, according to
Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is that the mutability of HIV may make the
treatment ineffective at any time.
</P>
<P>
World-renowned AIDS researchers like Professor David Ho, head
of the Diomand AIDS Center in New York, and Professor Rolf
Zinknagel, laureate of last year's Nobel Prize for Medicine,
delivered special lectures at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ho voiced optimism about continued progress in developing drugs
designed to inhibit the mutability of HIV. Dietrich noted it was
just a matter of time before a new generation of such drugs was
available.
</P>
<P>
The next European AIDS conference is scheduled for 1999 in
Lisbon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
