<HEADLINE> Former US Congressman Released From Custody </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Dan Rostenkowski, formerly a
powerful member of the U.S. House of Representatives, was freed
today after serving nearly 15 months of a mail fraud sentence.
</P>
<P>
Rostenkowski was released from a Salvation Army half-way house
in Chicago shortly after midnight. He drove away in a car with two
men, ignoring three television crews and a number of reporters who
had staked out the facility, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
He had been staying at the Salvation Army facility since his
release from a minimum-security prison camp in Wisconsin on August
19.
</P>
<P>
The former chairman of the tax-writing House of Representatives
Ways and Means Committee was indicted on 17 counts of embezzling
and misusing hundreds of thousands of dollars of government money
in the operation of his congressional office.
</P>
<P>
He had denied any wrongdoing, but in April 1996 pleaded guilty
to two felony counts of mail fraud. He was sentenced to 17 months
in prison and ordered to pay 100,000 dollars in fines and
restitution.
</P>
<P>
He will remain under probation for two years.
</P>
<P>
The 69-year-old Chicago Democrat, who served 18 House terms
before he was defeated after being indicted, entered jail in July
1996. 
</P>
