<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa to Keep Abreast With Information Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Kenya
Posts and Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC) said that "Africa
will not be marginalized in the emerging information society".
</P>
<P>
The KPTC Managing Director J. Mutai told the third
International Advertising Association (IAA) Africa Congress which
closed here today that his optimism was based on on-going
technological development and positive structural changes
currently being implemented in the sector of the continent.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the communications infrastructure in
Africa was the least developed in the world, saying that the
tele-density in Africa was less than 2 percent as compared to the
world average of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are more telephones in New York or in Tokyo than the
whole of Africa, he said, adding that quite a number of African
countries have no direct communication links with each other and
the intra-African traffic is invariably transited via Europe.
</P>
<P>
But, the Kenyan official noted, owing to the low tele-density
and rapidly growing population, Africa constituted the largest
demand and the world's biggest market for improved communication
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers of communication equipment throughout the world
have increasingly focused their attention on this vast market, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Mutai pointed out that the telecommunications sector in Africa
was undergoing fundamental change with more and more governments
liberalizing the sector and adopting multi-operator regulatory
regimes.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the existing Pan-African Telecommunication
Network connecting within Africa and with the rest of the world,
the majority of African countries are routing their traffic
through satellite communications, he said,
</P>
<P>
Many African countries have a growing desire to launch a
regional satellite system and have already set up the Regional
African Satellite Communication Organization which is based in
Abidjan, Mutai added.
</P>
<P>
Some telecommunication corporations are developing low and
medium earth orbiting satellite systems to connect Africa with
the rest of the world, and Iridium, one of the corporations,
plans to be first to launch its service by September 1998,
according to Mutai.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he pointed out, international connectivity
is also provided through submarine cables, adding that plans are
now underway to implement an Optical Fiber Submarine Cable around
the African continent, which is known as "Africa One".
</P>
<P>
He stressed at the four-day meeting that the challenge now was
to maintain this impetus for change if the sector was to attract
the substantial financial investments for Africa's
telecommunications and to ensure its connectivity to the rest of
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
