<HEADLINE> S. Korea's NKP Mounts Legal Action against Opposition Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's ruling New Korea
Party (NKP) today filed with prosecutors allegations of bribery,
tax evasion and libel against opposition leader Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
The NKP also handed the prosecution "concrete evidence" to back
its claims of corruption against Kim, the leader of the main
opposition National Congress for New Politics (NCNP).
</P>
<P>
The NKP charged that Kim had taken illegal bribes amounting to
more than 13 billion won (about 15 million U.S. dollars) from 10
business groups and had evaded taxes by stashing over 100 billion
won (about 110 million U.S. dollars) in secret funds kept in the
bank accounts of relatives and in-laws.
</P>
<P>
While the NKP is pushing hard to start an investigation into
its allegations about Kim's alleged slush funds, the prosecution
has not decided whether to begin an investigation.
</P>
<P>
A top prosecutor said his office will make the decision after a
very careful review of the NKP allegations, and repeated that a
probe would be launched only if concrete evidence emerged.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Kim's NCNP, however, said they had decided not to
file any counter-complaint against the NKP for the time being.
</P>
<P>
But one official said the party will file complaints against
President Kim Young-sam over his 1992 presidential campaign
spending, and against NKP presidential candidate Lee Hoi-chang for
his spending during the July NKP nomination contest if the
prosecution begins investigation of Kim.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP official said its counter-action may turn the
presidential race into a "war of character assassination."
</P>
<P>
Despite the aggressive allegations of corruption by the NKP,
Kim is still comfortably leading all opinion polls, well ahead of
the NKP's Lee, who is in a distant third place.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will hold presidential election in December this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
