<HEADLINE> China, Australia Sign Science, Technology Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- At the third Australia-China
Science and Technology Commission meeting here today, Li Xueyong,
China's Vice-Minister of the State Science and Technology
Commission, and Professor John Stocker, head of an Australian
Science and Technology delegation signed an agreement on
agriculture, pharmaceuticals, information technology,
environmental protection, new materials, energy resources,
semiconductors, and chemistry.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Stocker told Xinhua that priority is being given to
collaboration in satellite remote sensing technology, used for
studying crop output and plant diseases, and for environmental
protection projects.
</P>
<P>
Australian scientists and technologists discussed the progress
on projects started after the 2nd Commission meeting in Canberra
in 1994 with their Chinese counterparts during this four-day
meeting, Stocker said.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister Li said that China and Australia have much in
common because agriculture occupies an important place in their
economies. Both also have long coastlines and give priority to
high technology use.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the two will promote scientific and
technological co-operation in the Asia-Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, China and Australia signed a scientific and
technological co-operation agreement, and since then have
co-operated in agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry, nuclear
technology, communications, environmental protection, and other
areas.
</P>
<P>
Commission meeting are held every three years. The first was
held in June 1991 in Beijing, and the next is scheduled for
Australia in the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
