<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Vows not to Change Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
is not going to change the present government despite pressure by
some deputies of the State Duma, the lower house of the
parliament, a government official said today.
</P>
<P>
The official, a high-ranking representative of the Presidential
Administration, told reporters the president did not even intend
to discuss the issue with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
In no case would the president use First Deputy Prime Minister
Anatoly Chubais as an exchange card at talks with the opposition,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin today denied the
allegation by senior officials that he would have resigned if the
State Duma had voted no-confidence in the government, the Interfax
news service reported.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin told reporters that his personal rules of conduct
forbade him to intimidate anybody, even by the threat of his own
resignation.
</P>
<P>
The Federal government has "sufficient possibilities within the
bounds of the constitution and other laws to avoid a situation
whereby the government would hang in suspense for three months",
he said. The government, he added, would not work under such
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin also ruled out the possibility of any government
member leaving his or her post in the near future. He said: "There
is no need for sacking any ministers. All of them are working with
overload."
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, the president proposes his
candidate for prime minister to the Duma. The prime minister in
his turn proposes Cabinet members, and finally the president
approves the government composition by decree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
