<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Rupee Depreciation, Inevitable to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan
has depreciated the value of Pak rupee by a massive 8.71 percent
against the U.S. dollar in a bid to stimulate the stagnant
industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
This downward adjustment of rupee value is believed to be the
highest-ever devaluation of the local currency in one go during
the last 20 years. It was the sixth downward adjustment of rupee
against the dollar by the present government.
</P>
<P>
The announcement made by the government Wednesday came just
days before the executive board meeting of the International
Monetary (IMF) to consider the Enhanced Structural Adjustment
Facility/Extended Fund Facility program for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Economists here are of the view that the Pakistani government
was reluctant to go for devaluation and argued with the IMF that
as the mark up rates are being reduced and the inflation rate has
been contained, there is no need to devalue the local currency.
</P>
<P>
However, the continuous decline in exports and unsatisfactory
results of the reforms have forced the government to follow the
IMF suggestion.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed that the latest devaluation was spurred by
the Pak rupee appreciation against the regional currencies which
was causing decline in Pakistan's exports.
</P>
<P>
A report today in the major English daily, The Nation, said the
mounting pressure for devaluation was coming from exporters on the
plea that exports were not picking up because of the inflation
differential between Pakistan and its major trading partners,
especially those in Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, there remains a long and inconclusive debate in
Pakistan for and against devaluation of the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The pro camp argues that the inflation differential between
Pakistan and its major markets, as well as between Pakistan and
its major competitors in those markets, necessitates periodic
readjustment of rupee to keep the exports competitive, thereby
easing pressure on the balance of trade.
</P>
<P>
The anti camp, however, argues that the inherited structural
bias of Pakistan's economy towards an import substitution strategy
of industrialization means that Pakistan's dependence on imported
plant and raw materials for such industry will always negate or
nullify whatever healthy impact devaluation may have on exports.
</P>
<P>
The trade and industry organizations have shown concern over
the large-scale devaluation as, according to them, the cost of
Pakistan's imports especially that of the industrial raw material
will go up and lead to higher prices of the finished products.
</P>
<P>
The consumers associations have condemned the action as all the
consumer durables will go out of reach of common man. They are
skeptical of the rise in exports as all the past devaluation
failed to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
Defending the decision, Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said that
the Pak rupee is linked with the dollar, the latter has gained
considerable strength in terms of other currencies, and the rupee
has thus effectively been appreciated against these currencies.
</P>
<P>
Another external factor of some urgency was created by the
currency upheaval in Southeast Asia since July, said Aziz, adding
that any further delay would have put Pakistan into trouble.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Pakistan would not depreciate its currency any
more during the current fiscal year. He also asserted the
devaluation would neither affect the common man nor flame
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The cost of transportation, electricity and food items will
remain the same which would not put any additional burden on the
common man, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no doubt the exchange rate adjustment has
consequences in terms of higher prices of imported goods,
including petroleum, and higher debt-servicing costs.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that the most important impact of the
exchange rate adjustment will be on manufactured exports,
particularly high-valued textiles and many non-traditional
exports.
</P>
<P>
However, as the finance minister claims, the latest move will
enable greater exports when Pakistan is likely to have larger
exportable surpluses due to improved agricultural outlook which
provides the basis for export-led growth in the economy.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed that the exchange rate adjustment will
encourage Pakistan's import-substituting activities. Coupled with
the other measures, this action is expected to provide a major
boost to industrial and agriculture production and promote greater
employment and investment in Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
