<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Breaks out in Northern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting has broken out
in Mazar-e-Sharif, capital of the northern Afghan province of
Balkh, between forces of northern Uzbek warlord Rashid Dostum and
General Abdul Malik.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here this evening, Commander Juma
Khan of Hezb-Islami Hikmatyar and Hezb-i-Wahdat (Khalili group)
supported Malik's forces in the fighting, while Hezb-i-Wahdat
Akbari group and former defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood's
fighters supported Dostum, who was ousted by his one-time
supporter Malik in May.
</P>
<P>
Malik briefly sided with the Taliban militia in May to oust
Dostum, but later joined the anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the clashes took place in the center of the
city this morning. But so far there have been no reports on the
losses in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, forces of the Afghan Taliban militia captured
Shaekhali district of the northern province of Parwan, where
Masood's forces faced a defeat, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Masood's forces launched a heavy attack in
Takhar province on the Taliban positions and claimed a success in
the fighting, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
