<HEADLINE> Seoul Prosecution Appeals President's Son's Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korean prosecutors filed an
appeal today against the three-year sentence handed down by a
district court to Kim Hyun-chul, the second son of President Kim
Young-sam.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution asked for a firmer punishment for the junior
Kim, and claimed he should have been found guilty on one
additional count which the court deemed him innocent of.
</P>
<P>
Kim was sentenced Monday for bribery and tax evasion, and fined
1.44 billion won (1.57 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors, who had earlier demanded that Kim serve seven-year
imprisonment, said the charge involved money Kim allegedly
received from the Dooyang Group in return for business favors.
</P>
<P>
But the district court said there was no evidence to support
the prosecution's accusation.
</P>
<P>
In another move, the president's son also appealed his sentence
to the Seoul District Court Wednesday, arguing that it was
unreasonable for the court to find him guilty of evading taxes
which he was never asked to pay.
</P>
<P>
It is the first case in South Korea in which someone has been
sentenced over tax payments in connection with "political funds"
received. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
