<HEADLINE> World Champion Deng Yaping Retains National Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- World and Olympic champion
Deng Yaping retained her singles title in the women's table tennis
tournament at the Eighth National Games here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese veteran paddler with four Olympic golds beat Wang
Hui of Heilongjiang province to award the gold to her native Henan
province in straight sets 21-12, 21-7, 21-15.
</P>
<P>
With defensive tactics, Wang Hui surprised her opponents by
entering the finals after victories over ninth-ranked Wu Na and
eighth-ranked Wang Chen.
</P>
<P>
However, Deng Yaping, the top player in the world, sacrificed
her fast attacks for loops and ripped the rhythm of Wang Hui
through cunning drops en route to her final victory.
</P>
<P>
Wang Hui still remained as a phenomenon in the tournament after
she won her singles title in the National Championships last year,
the first time in a decade for a chopper to achieve such a feat.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning's Wang Nan won the women's bronze medal by defeating
world number two Li Ju of Jiangsu 21-10, 21-13 and 21-12, who was
eliminated by Wang Hui in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Olympic men's singles champion Liu Luoliang paired with veteran
Wang Tao to retain the doubles title for the Chinese Army by
ousting local tandem Feng Zhe and Wang Liqin 21-13, 21-10, 20-22,
21-13.
</P>
<P>
Chen Longcan, who won China's first men's doubles Olympic gold
with Wei Qingguang in the Seoul Games in 1988, paired with Zhang
Yu to take the bronze for Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
In the mixed doubles finals, Jiangsu's Qin Zhijian and Yang
Ying captured the gold by beating Henan's Meng Xianjian and Zhang
Hui 21-13, 21-18, 17-21, 21-9.
</P>
<P>
The third place went to Wang Tao and Wang Yue of the Chinese
Army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
