<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Virus Discovery Threatens Pig Transplant Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Two previously unidentified
viruses have been found in pig organs, raising a new hurdle for
pig-to-human transplants.
</P>
<P>
The viruses, which were reported today in the science journal,
Nature, form part of the pig's own genetic complement, meaning
that it will be very difficult to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
They can cause leukaemia in monkeys, cats and birds and are
thought to be able to infect humans.
</P>
<P>
Tens of millions of pounds have been invested in attempts to
raise pigs genetically so that their organs can be transplanted to
humans.
</P>
<P>
The new findings are published by scientists from the Institute
for Medical Research in Mill Hill, northwest London.
</P>
<P>
They concluded that, because the viruses were so common in a
wide range of pigs, "the breeding of virus-free pigs, if at all
feasible, will represent a complex task." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yehudi Menuhin Conducts Chinese Orchestra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- World-renowned violinist and
conductor Yehudi Menuhin conducted the first concert of his third
China tour this evening with the China National Symphony Orchestra
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The performance was of Edward Elgar's violin concerto and
Brahms' Symphony No.4.
</P>
<P>
A recording that Menuhin made of Elgar's violin concerto sixty
five years ago is still the definitive version.
</P>
<P>
This evening, however, a young Chinese violist, Hu Kun from
southwest China's Sichuan province, one of Menuhin's favorite
students, took over with the violin, and Menuhin took the baton.
</P>
<P>
Menuhin told the press earlier that the special thing about the
performance is that the violinist can show his feelings as a
Chinese about this musical piece. Their close co-ordination could
be seen throughout the entire two-hour performance.
</P>
<P>
Hu entered the Menuhin Music Academy in Gstaad in 1984 and has
worked together with Menuhin up to the present.
</P>
<P>
Menuhin said that the members of the National Symphony
Orchestra, which he is working with for the first time, are very
warm, intelligent, and quick to understand him. "It's such a nice
feeling that we can share musical thoughts and experiences
together," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Seeks WTO Ruling on Chilean Liquor Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union's executive body, today asked the World Trade
Organization (WTO) to rule whether Chilean taxation of alcoholic
beverages violates world trade rules.
</P>
<P>
The Commission is complaining about the wide gap between the
tax rates imposed on imported spirits compared with local produce.
</P>
<P>
Imported whisky faces a 70-percent tax and vodka and the
majority of other imported spirits face a 30 percent tax, whereas
local alcoholic beverage face only a 25 percent tax.
</P>
<P>
A local product, pisco, represents about 80 percent of the
total market for spirits inside the country.
</P>
<P>
Surveys on consumption of imported whisky and pisco between
1982 and 1995 showed that the market share of European whisky
fell from 19 percent to less than 3 percent while the market share
of pisco more than trebled.
</P>
<P>
The EC argued that the difference Chile effectively
discriminates against imported spirits and therefore breaches WTO
rules.
</P>
<P>
As a WTO member, Chile is committed to not discriminate against
imported products by internal taxation.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean case bears a striking resemblance to the case
levied against Japan in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Canada jointly resorted to the WTO
dispute settlement mechanism against the Japanese liquor tax
regime which was found to be incompatible with WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Japan announced a reform of its liquor tax regime
so that it no longer taxes imported products significantly higher
than the domestic produce.
</P>
<P>
European global exports of spirits amount to about four billion
ECUs (4.4 billion U.S. dollars) a year and employs 50,000 people
among EU countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
