<HEADLINE> United Opposition Party Formed in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A united opposition party was
formed here today with its leaders expressing optimism that it
will beat the ruling Lakas-NUCD party headed by President Fidel
Ramos in next year's presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
The party, Struggle of the Nationalist Filipino Masses, was
made up by three opposition parties, namely, the Filipino Masses
led by Vice President Joseph Estrada, the Struggle of the
Democratic Filipino chaired by Senator Edgardo Angara and the
Nationalist People's Coalition headed by Senate President Ernesto
Maceda.
</P>
<P>
At the founding ceremony, the leaders and more than 3,000
members of the party ratified a covenant of unity, vowing to
support whoever is chosen as the party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
A convention to choose the new party's candidate in the 1998
polls will be held on November 27, about six months before the
country's national elections.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the participants elected Maceda the party's
interim national chairman, Angara the interim national president
and Senator Oriando Mercado the secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who enjoyed a higher popularity in surveys, urged his
party-mates to seize the opportunity to empower the people by
offering a genuine political alternative in the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
The united opposition party promised food security, jobs, mass
housing, better education and tough action against corruption if
it takes power.  
</P>
</TEXT>
