<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs To Exploit More Overseas Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- China's petroleum and natural
gas production can no longer meet the needs of its rapidly growing
economy and needs to exploit more foreign oil, an official in
charge of the country's overseas oil engineering programs said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Qin Anmin, manager of the China Petroleum Engineering
Construction Co., told the 15th World Petroleum Congress that
China was an oil exporter a few years ago but is now an
importer. It produced 157 million tons of crude oil last year and
imported some 20 million tons.
</P>
<P>
It is possible to do this for a short period of time, he said,
but not for long, not only because of the cost, but also because
a stable oil supply is hard to guarantee.
</P>
<P>
So, China has no choice but to open up more and make a greater
effort in developing overseas oilfields to share the world oil
resources. This is a strategic option for sustainable
growth. Building stable petroleum and gas production bases is also
necessary for improved distribution of China's oil and gas
resources, he said.
</P>
<P>
The China National Petroleum Corp. and his engineering
construction company have bought into oilfields in Canada, Peru,
Thailand, Kazakhstan, Venezuela, Malaysia, and Pakistan. Last
year, China had 700,000 tons of crude oil coming from overseas
co-operative oilfields.
</P>
<P>
The China Petroleum Engineering Construction Co. has signed 230
overseas oil and technological service contracts. The company has
completed 1.6 billion US dollars worth of contracts, and has been
selected during 1994-1997 as one of the most important oil
engineering contractors in the world, the manager said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
