<HEADLINE> International Arts Show Held in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's first International
Arts Fair that opened here today, has 5,000 paintings from
Switzerland, the United States, China and other countries in an
8,200-sq.m. area in the World Trade Plaza.
</P>
<P>
The six-day fair has oil paintings, traditional Chinese
paintings, watercolors, calligraphy, and sculptures on display.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland's Galerie Sagg Arah brought 26 paintings, including
works of Picasso and contemporary artists. Georges Marci, the
gallery's owner, said they are looking for potentially successful
young Chinese artists and give them worldwide exposure.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the works of Picasso, one can find works of
Renoir, Chagall, and some great Chinese artists like Wu Changshuo,
Xu Beihong, Zhang Daqian, Fu Baoshi, Pan Tianshou, Qi Baishi, and
Feng Zikai.
</P>
<P>
Ding Shaoguang, a famous Chinese-American painter, rented a
showroom for himself. "Many foreigners have listed Shanghai at the
top of the most prosperous cities in the 21st century because of
its cultural background," said the artist, who was born in China's
Shaanxi province.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Dawei, vice dean of the Arts College at Shanghai
University, said, "As an international metropolis, Shanghai
improves its cultural function along with rapid economic
development."
</P>
<P>
Some of the works will be auctioned during the fair, according
to the organizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
