<HEADLINE> Italian Government Wins Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government won a
confidence vote in the lower house this afternoon, restoring its
majority and formally ending the political crisis triggered by the
resignation of Prime Minister Romano Prodi a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Prodi announced his resignation on October 9, following the
Communist Refoundation Party's refusal to soften its opposition to
rewriting the deficit-cutting draft.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's government depended on the Communist Refoundation Party
in the lower house to pass legislation.
</P>
<P>
In today's vote, the left-wing Communist Refoundation voted
with the Olive Tree governing alliance in the confidence test.
</P>
<P>
The result of the vote was seen as a foregone conclusion as the
government and Communist Refoundation reached an agreement earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the party was to support the
16.6-billion-U.S.-dollar budget. And in exchange, the government
was to reduce the working week to 35 hours by 2001, reduce
spending cuts by 330 million U.S. dollars, protect pensions for
blue-collar workers, and open consultations on economic and social
policy.
</P>
<P>
The confidence debate will move to the Senate later this
afternoon followed by a confidence motion in the evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
