<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Tightened in Sri Lanka's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Defense Ministry
said today that security in the capital Colombo has been
strengthened and contingency plans have been put into operation to
meet any further Tamil rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
The ministry in a press release declared that measures have
been taken by the security forces to ensure the safety of life and
property of all citizens and visitors residing in Colombo and
other areas of the island nation.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
carried out Wednesday morning's bombing attack because it has
become "extremely desperate" with regard to its losses in the
battle field in the north.
</P>
<P>
Over 2,500 rebels have been killed and a large number injured
in fighting since government troops launched the military
operation "Jayasikuru" (Certain Victory) on May 13, the ministry
noted.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also said that the explosion came in the wake of
the declaration by the United States that the LTTE and other 29
organizations were on its terrorist organization list.
</P>
<P>
"In desperation, the LTTE has chosen to explode a vehicle bomb
at the car park of a tourist hotel without giving any
consideration to the fact that there were many foreign nationals,"
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
A truck loaded with explosives rammed into the car park of the
Galadari Hotel in the business center of Colombo Wednesday morning
before it exploded.
</P>
<P>
So far 16 people were killed in the incident, including five
rebels shot dead by security forces in crossfire after the
explosion. A total of 108 people were injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
