<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Colombo Returns to Normal After Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan capital of
Colombo returned to normal today after a powerful bombing ripped
through a downtown district Wednesday morning, and repair work has
been underway in the shattered business district.
</P>
<P>
The explosion site in the car park of Galadari Hotel, a
five-star landmark in business district Colombo 1, was still
cordoned off. Though there are still many heavily armed soldiers
and policemen, their number has been reduced greatly.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the hotels and other damaged buildings
surrounding the park were reckoning the losses. Employees were
allowed to return to their smashed offices to clear up the mess
after they showed their ID cards at the check points.
</P>
<P>
Most of the debris on the main road near the affected area has
been removed, and trucks were called in to take rubbles and
destroyed vehicles away.
</P>
<P>
In other parts of the city, offices, shops and markets opened
as usual and people went about their business as if nothing had
happened in this city.
</P>
<P>
Police sources confirmed a total of 16 people died in the
incident, including five rebels shot dead by security forces.
Among the dead was a foreigner whose nationality was not disclosed
yet.
</P>
<P>
A total of 108 people, including 32 foreigners, were injured in
the incident, police said. Among them, 24 were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
One terrorist suspect was captured alive by the security
forces, police said.
</P>
<P>
Both the Galadari Hotel and the Hilton Hotel are closed
temporarily and their guests have been transferred to other hotels
in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Yasmin Cader, public relations manager of Hilton, said her
hotel could have to be closed for at least three to four months
for repairs.
</P>
<P>
World Trade Center sources said their technical staff could not
carry out their survey in detail at the rear side of the building
due to fear of falling glass and windows. A large section of the
rear wall, about 10 meters high, collapsed in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
The Colombo Stock Exchange housed in the trade center suspended
trading today.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations are still underway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
