<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Record Holder Liu Crashed in National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- World record holder Liu Limin
made an early exit in the preliminaries of the women's 100 meters
butterfly, creating the biggest upset in the pool at the Eighth
National Games here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The event was won by Qu Yun of the Chinese Army with a time of
59.36 seconds, followed by Shanghai's Cai Huijue in 59.47 and
Liaoning's Ning Bo in 1:00.08.
</P>
<P>
Liu, silver medalist in the event in the Atlanta Olympic Games,
finished fourth in the group eight heats, failing to qualify for
the final eight.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, she has made full preparation for the National Games.
Maybe she took it too easy for the preliminaries which eventually
became a fatal mistake," said Zhou Ming, vice head coach of the
Chinese national swimming team.
</P>
<P>
"It's a pity. But she still has a chance in the 200m butterfly.
She is the best Chinese swimmer in the event," Zhou said of the
veteran, member of the world record holders in the women's 4X100m
team medley in both long and short course with He Cihong, Dai
Guohong and Le Jingyi.
</P>
<P>
Liu also established a world record in the 100m butterfly in
the World Short Course Swimming Championships in Rio de Janeiro,
Brazil, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 400m freestyle, Jin Hao took a sweet revenge over
local favorite Xiong Guoming to win the gold.
</P>
<P>
Jin, 18, who finished second after Xiong in the 400m individual
medley on Tuesday, clocked a new national mark of three minutes
54.78.
</P>
<P>
Xiong won the silver with 3:55.13 while former national mark
holder Deng Qingsong settled for the third with 3:55.48.
</P>
<P>
Jin, who stands 1.85 meters, trailed Deng in the first 300
meters, but made a spectacular dash in the last 100 meters to take
the gold.
</P>
<P>
"I'm excited to win the first gold for Shandong since this is
the first time I have won a gold in a major competition," Jin
said. "I am confident I can achieve good results in other events."
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200m breaststroke, Zhang Yi of Shanghai captured
the gold in 2:26.74. The silver went to Yuan Yuan of the Chinese
Army and Mi Tong of Jiangsu finished third, who were timed 2:29.34
and 2:30.62 respectively.
</P>
<P>
"I was upset in the 100m finals wherein I didn't swim my best
time. Today I'm very satisfied with my performance," said the
19-year-old teenager.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100m backstroke gold was won by Shanghai's Wang Wei
in 56.53 seconds while the local foursome also claimed the men's
4X100 freestyle relay in 3:27.32. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
