<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 1,500 Steles Discovered in Southern Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Over 1,500 steles have
been discovered in various localities of southern Ethiopia, a
report from the Ethiopian News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the culture and information bureau of the
South Ethiopian People's National State as saying that the
steles, estimated to be up to 1,200 years old, were erected to
commemorate wars, transition of tribal authority and war heroes.
</P>
<P>
Metasebiya Bekele, an expert from the bureau, was quoted as
saying that the tradition of erecting stone steles is almost a
bygone practice, and is now exercised only by the Konos
nationality, which observed a transfer of authority by erecting a
two-meter stone last year.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 of the afore-mentioned steles have been recognized
by the state's trade, industry and tourism bureau and are being
visited by tourists, the expert noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
