<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain, Australia, Maldives Condemn Colombo Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain, Australia and the
Maldives have condemned the bombing in Sri Lanka's capital Colombo
Wednesday and extended their sympathy to families of innocent
victims in the blast.
</P>
<P>
In a message sent to Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman
Kadirgamar today, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said that
Britain "strongly condemns such acts of terrorism" and expressed
his deepest sympathy to the families of the innocent victims of
the deplorable incident.
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign and Commonwealth Office spokesman said: "We
strongly condemn this latest bomb outrage in Colombo, as we do all
acts of terrorism in Sri Lanka and elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said he was
shocked and distressed by the bomb attack in Colombo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian government has made clear on many occasions
that it condemns unequivocally all acts of terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, "We do not live in a world any longer where
people are prepared to tolerate acts of terror, and acts of
terrorism are matters of deep and abiding concern to the people of
Australia and the government of Australia."
</P>
<P>
Maumoon Abdul Gayoom, president of the Republic of the
Maldives, said in a letter to Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga: "It was with deep shock and sorrow that I learnt
about the bomb blast in Colombo. The government and the people of
the Maldives deplore all acts of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
A truck loaded with explosives blasted in the business center
of Colombo Wednesday morning, killing 11 people and injuring 108
others. Five rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam who
carried out the attack were later shot dead in crossfire with the
security forces and a sixth was captured.  
</P>
</TEXT>
