<HEADLINE> Islamic Group in Algeria Decides to Lay Down Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The "FIDA," a group of the
Islamic Front for Armed Struggle of Algeria has decided to suspend
its combat operations all over Algeria starting from today.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper "Al-Khaber" today quoted a statement issued
Wednesday by the "FIDA" as saying that this decision came in
response to an appeal by both Madani Mezeraq, commander of the
Islamic Salvation Army, the armed wing of the Islamic Salvation
Front and Ali Ben Hajer, chief of the Islamic League for Preaching
and Jihad for laying down arms.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Salvation Front, better known by its French
initials FIS, is a banned party leading an anti-government
insurgency which has raged since Algerian authorities canceled
1992 elections the FIS was poised to win.
</P>
<P>
Mezeraq issued on September 21 a statement ordering his men to
stop armed struggle as of October 1st, while Hajer, in a statement
issued on October 10, declared his organization's operations
suspended as of October 16.
</P>
<P>
The "FIDA," an Islamic group established in Algeria in 1992 and
banned in 1993, has been carrying out terrorist operations against
both the government and civilians.
</P>
<P>
A total of 75,000 people were killed in violence during the
five-year-old insurgency in Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
