<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Ask for Petroleum Industry Co-operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries are
appealing for better international cooperation in the oil business
at the 15th World Petroleum Congress, which closed here today.
</P>
<P>
Representatives said today that they are in urgent need of
assistance in funds and technology from international
organizations and developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Gabon's energy minister pointed out that, although African
countries are rich in oil and gas, their oil industries are
stalemated because of a lack of funding, and they are making an
effort to explore new oilfields and improve facilities. They are
also talking of preferential policies for investors, but they need
better overseas cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Similar sentiments were expressed by the head of Mali's
delegation. Algeria's energy minister also said that co-operation
can reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
Marcos Leon, Cuba's Minister of Basic Industry, told Xinhua
that his country has more than 40 agreements with foreign
companies and has opened 13 oilfields. He said that Cuba hopes to
get more advanced technology to improve its oil business to reduce
imports.
</P>
<P>
Development and co-operation are the common themes of the oil
business, saya Janeshwar Mishra, Minister for Petroleum and
Natural Gas of India, which especially wants greater ties with the
Middle East, Africa, the Commonwealth of Independent States, and
Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tao, the vice-head of the congress, said that China is
willing to provide experience and technology to increase oil
exploration, and wants to develop trade relations with more
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
