<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Camp Launching New Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition parties
are launching a new campaign to oust Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu over the current diplomatic and coalition crises caused
by Netanyahu's policies.
</P>
<P>
Leading opposition Labor Party's head Ehud Barak has been
holding meetings with party leaders within the ruling coalition
and even key figures from the Netanyahu-led Likud Party, in an
attempt to gain support from 80 lawmakers needed to oust
Netanyahu without holding new election for the Knesset
(Parliament).
</P>
<P>
Under the Basic Law that went into effect in last year's
elections, 80 Knesset members can automatically oust the prime
minister without holding new election for the Knesset; If 61
Knesset members vote against the government, it has to step down
to pave the way for holding new elections both for the prime
minister and the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Labor sources as saying that Barak had
found "broad support" both within the coalition and the Likud
camp. The report did not elaborate on the number of supporters,
but it is believed to be difficult for Barak to garner the
support of 80 Knesset members.
</P>
<P>
In his own initiative, Yossi Sarid, leader of another major
opposition party Meretz, today issued a call to 97 Knesset
members, who do not belong to the religious bloc, to make public
declaration against the proposed conversion law and religious
council law that discriminate against the secular community.
</P>
<P>
Barak's campaign to oust Netanyahu came following the
diplomatic crisis triggered by the failed attempt to assassinate
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) leader Khaled Mashaal in
Jordan last month, which has strained Israeli diplomatic
relations with Jordan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was responsible for ordering the attack by two
Israeli agents who used forged Canadian passports and has been
widely criticized for his arrogance and misjudgement.
</P>
<P>
Following the Mashaal affair, some centrist coalition parties
such as The Third Way and Yisrael Ba'aliya Party, have called for
setting up a national unity government between Likud and the
Labor.
</P>
<P>
The latest government crisis centered over the impending
passing by the Knesset of the conversion law and religious
council law, which only recognize conversions conducted by
Orthodox Rabbis and will exclude non-Orthodox Jews from local
religious councils.
</P>
<P>
The influential religious bloc within the current coalition
has threatened to topple the government if it refuses their
demand to enact the proposed laws.
</P>
<P>
American Jewry, mostly belonging to the non-Orthodox Reform
and Conservative movements, are especially angered by the
discriminating laws, threatening to withhold financial support to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
If the proposed conversion law and religious council law are
passed under the pressure of the Orthodox parties, it will
further deepen the rift within the Israeli society and have wide
repercussions on the current government.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Meretz, which consider them to be protectors of the
secular interests, are expected to escalate their pressure on
the government so to force it to step down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Begin Aid Flights to PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia announced today it
is to begin emergency aid flights into the worst-affected areas of
famine-stricken Papua New Guinea (PNG) early next week.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Affairs Minister Alexander Downer said the
flights would begin early next week to areas which can only be
reached by air after Australia's offer was accepted by the PNG
government.
</P>
<P>
"Like many in Australia I am concerned to learn that 500,000
people are facing immediate hardship from the country's widespread
frosts and drought," Downer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The flights will carry high priority food aid, like rice and
flour, to the areas at greatest risk," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
But the foreign minister did not say how much food the
Australian government will provide to PNG, which gained
independence from Australia in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The emergency aid flights will concentrate on the worst
affected areas where the situation is described as extreme with no
food available at all, water very short, widespread illness and
young children and older people dying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
