<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Diplomatic Position and Guidelines (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local diplomats noted that the guidelines will guarantee
China's implementation of Deng Xiaoping's diplomatic thinking and
the nation's independent foreign policy of peace. China will carry
out the guidelines in the following manner:
</P>
<P>
First, China will pursue an independent foreign policy. Deng
Xiaoping consistently reiterated that developing countries cannot
develop without self-respect and national independence, and that
state sovereignty and security should be regarded as the top
priority.
</P>
<P>
The steady enhancement of China's international status and its
growing influence and prominence in international arena can be
attributed to its persistence in independence and self-reliance
and proceeding from the fundamental interests of the Chinese
people and of the world's people in dealing with international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Second, opposing hegemony and safeguarding world peace
represent China's consistent stand and are a long-term task facing
the world's progressive forces.
</P>
<P>
The Cold War has ended, but hegemony and power politics still
pose a threat to world peace and stability. Superpowers play power
politics with small countries from time to time and it is nothing
new that strong nations bully smaller nations, and rich countries
bully poor countries. Superpowers continue to wantonly interfere
in the internal affairs of and aggravated the situation in other
countries.
</P>
<P>
China upholds the equality of all countries, regardless of
whether a nation is large or small, rich or poor, strong or
weak. China will unremittingly oppose hegemony and power politics,
and will safeguard world peace and development. China, a permanent
member of the United Nations Security Council, will continue to
play a positive role toward this end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Diplomatic Position and Guidelines (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin's report
to the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China,
held one month ago, outlined the international situation and
formulated guidelines for China's foreign policy in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang outlined 10 guidelines for China's diplomacy:
</P>
<P>
-- Pursuing an independent foreign policy of peace;
</P>
<P>
-- Opposing hegemony and safeguarding world peace;
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting the establishment of a just and rational
international political and economic order;
</P>
<P>
-- Respecting the diversity of the world;
</P>
<P>
-- Upholding the good-neighbor policy;
</P>
<P>
-- Further strengthening solidarity and cooperation with other
Third World countries;
</P>
<P>
-- Improving and developing relations with developed countries
on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence;
</P>
<P>
-- Upholding the principle of equality and mutual benefit, and
conducting extensive trade, economic and technological cooperation
and scientific and cultural exchanges with all countries and
regions;
</P>
<P>
-- Actively participating in multilateral diplomatic activities;
</P>
<P>
-- Developing new types of interparty relations, exchanges and
cooperation with political parties in other countries based on the
principles of independence, full equality, mutual respect and
noninterference in the internal affairs of another nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Position and Guidelines of China's Diplomacy (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fourth, efforts to improve and develop relations with all
countries should be carried out on the basis of the Five
Principles of Peaceful Coexistence.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign policy based on strengthening its solidarity
and cooperation with other developing countries is determined by
historical experience and the needs of future development.
</P>
<P>
China and other developing countries share the same historical
experiences, and face the common task of safeguarding their
independence and sovereignty, as well as promoting economic
development.
</P>
<P>
China and other developing countries, which have shared a
common fate for many years, have supported each other, united
closely and effectively maintained their political and economic
interests.
</P>
<P>
Despite dramatic changes in the international situation, China
cannot and will not change its policy on strengthening its
solidarity and cooperation with other developing countries. China
will forever belong to the Third World.
</P>
<P>
China and western countries have different social systems,
ideology, histories and cultures. However, all sides share
extensive common interests, and there are broad prospects for
mutually beneficiary cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China has consistently held that it is normal for different
countries to have different viewpoints on certain issues. However,
it is more important for all countries to focus on long-term
interests, while seeking mutual respect, equality and benefits, as
well as noninterference in internal affairs of other nations,
friendly coexistence and common development.
</P>
<P>
Facts prove that threatening or imposing sanctions on other
countries, or otherwise frequently exerting unilateral pressure,
are no way conducive to resolving issues, but instead will sharpen
contradictions and damage the interests of all parties concerned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Diplomatic Position and Guidelines (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mankind's progress depends on recognizing and respecting the
diversity of the world and on peaceful co-existance among the
peoples in various countries with different social system,
ideology and lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
Any nation's attempt to ignore the diversity of the world and
to impose a self-proclaimed superior mode, social system, ideology
or lifestyle on others will arouse disgust and opposition from
other nations.
</P>
<P>
Third, China will work diligently for the establishment of a
peaceful, stable, fair and rational new world political and
economic order. The people of the world have long been demanding
the dismantling of the old international order and the
establishment of a new order.
</P>
<P>
China's has maintained a clear-cut position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
China holds that the new international order should be
established on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence and should conform with the purposes and principles of
the UN Charter.
</P>
<P>
The new international order should be based on the following
contents: All countries should have the right to select their own
development mode according to their own national conditions, with
other countries having no right to interfere; All countries should
be equal members of the international community and no country
should seek hegemony or practice power politics; Conflicts between
different countries should be resolved through peaceful means, and
no country should resort to force or threat to use force;
Economic, scientific, technological and cultural exchanges and
cooperation should be strengthened and expanded on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit in an effort to promote common
development and prosperity; Unequal and discriminative policies,
practices and economic sanctions related to economic and trade
ties should be opposed.
</P>
<P>
The international economy is becoming increasingly
interdependent and the economies of the North and South are
closely linked. Developed countries should create favorable
conditions to ensure the growth of developing countries. This will
be also conducive to the economic development of the developed
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
