<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets World Record With Its Dam Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- For 24 hours, heavy-duty trucks
Wednesday lined both sides of two coffer-dams and dumped hundreds
of tons of rocks into the Yangtze River for the Three Gorges Dam,
while a line of ships did their part to fill the river with rocks.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze will be officially blocked on November 8.
</P>
<P>
The 1,800 workers who were part of the exercise said that they
are resolved to challenge the record set in 1978 by Brazil and
Paraguay at the Itaipu Hydro-Electric Power Station, which is the
world's largest. Workers there dumped 146,000 cu.m. of rock into
the river in a 24 hour-period.
</P>
<P>
In a 24-hour period, 170,000 cu.m. of water passed through the
Yangtze every second, compared with 9,000 cu.m. in other large dam
projects.
</P>
<P>
The dam work narrowed the openings on the two coffer-dams to
190 meters and 255 meters, from the 260 meters and 270 meters
during the second stage of the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
