<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Surplus Reported in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria recorded a trade surplus
of 1.31 billion U.S. dollars in the first two months of this
year, according to latest statistics of the Central Bank of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Bank figures show that foreign exchange inflow to the economy
stood at 2.75 billion dollars, compared with the outflow of 1.44
billion dollars during the two months.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil is still the chief foreign exchange earner as
receipt from oil increased to 1.3 billion dollars in February
from 1.22 billion dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the favorable balance of trade position was
equally responsible for the increase in the country's external
reserve during the two months.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's foreign reserve stood at 5.86 billion dollars in
February, compared to 5.15 billion dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
To cater to the needs of domestic production and consumption,
Nigeria also spent a total of 482.3 million dollars on importing
raw materials and finished goods in the January-February period.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for 35 percent of the total foreign
exchange outpayment for both visible and invisible imports during
the same period, according to the Central Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
