<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adherence to Theory of Primary Stage of Socialism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) ended last month with a call
for persevering adherence to the theory of the primary stage of
socialism.
</P>
<P>
People from all social strata responded positively to the call
by noting that adherence to the important theory will have
far-reaching significance on China's future development.
</P>
<P>
An authoritative theoretician regarded the theory of the
primary stage of socialism serves as an ideological weapon for
unifying thinking, clarifying doubt and eliminating
interference. He said that adherence to the theory is vital for
China's reform, opening-up and modernization.
</P>
<P>
The concept of the primary stage of socialism was advanced 10
years ago during the 13th National Party Congress. Jiang Zemin
re-iterated the theory and outlined basic guidelines during the
15th congress.
</P>
<P>
The theory of the primary stage of socialism includes two major
implications: China practices socialism and must adhere to the
system; Chinese socialism is still in the primary stage and cannot
overstep this primary stage.
</P>
<P>
Nine main features mark the historical period:
</P>
<P>
-- The underdeveloped economic status will gradually be cast
aside and China will basically realize modernization;
</P>
<P>
-- China will be transformed from an agricultural country which
depends heavily on manual labor to an industrial nation featuring
modern agriculture and a highly developed service industry;
</P>
<P>
-- The existin natural or semi-natural economy will move
steadily to a highly-developed market economy.
</P>
<P>
-- The high proportion of illiteracy and semi-illiteracy will
be replaced by a relatively developed advanced science, technology
education and culture, and;
</P>
<P>
-- All Chinese people will gradually gain wealth, compared to
the current situation in which people living in need account for a
high proportion of the total population and living standards as a
whole are rather low;
</P>
<P>
-- Gaps in regional economic and cultural development will
gradually be narrowed;
</P>
<P>
-- Reforms will lead to the establishment and perfection of a
socialist market economy and socialist democratic political system;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
