<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Colombo Bombing, Multi-purpose Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The powerful blast which ripped
through a downtown district of Sri Lanka's capital Colombo
Wednesday was aimed at retaliating the U.S. announcement of
listing the Tamil tigers as terrorists, local analysts said today.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE),
which was declared as a terrorist group by the U.S. government on
October 8, chose the downtown business center as their target of
bombing because there were some 12 American military officers
living in the adjoining Hilton Hotel, which was badly damaged in
the explosion, sources close to the military told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The suicidal truck bombing took place early Wednesday morning
in downtown Colombo, killing at least five including one foreigner
and wounding another 105 including 29 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Military sources said the rebels planned to kill those
Americans in this bombing attack after they got learned of the
American officers' whereabouts through their intelligence network
in the army.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Americans were on a secret trip in Colombo
to help the Sri Lankan government troops bring an end to the
14-year-long ethnic war, which has claimed more than 55,000 lives.
They arrived last week.
</P>
<P>
Industrial Development Minister C.V. Gunaratna Wednesday
denounced the bombing and pointed out that the attack was an
attempt to retaliate the U.S. government's declaration to put the
LTTE on the terrorist organization list.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madelene Albright on October 8
announced that the LTTE, along with 29 other organizations in the
world, would be barred from entering and raising funds in the U.S.
 Anybody who contributes to the LTTE in the U.S. will be charged
with criminal offense under the ban.
</P>
<P>
The wider consequence beyond the announcement is that "other
governments would be requested by the U.S. government to take due
heed to this declaration and to take supportive measures in their
own countries," said Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar.
</P>
<P>
The bombing could serve other purposes as well, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The 39-story World Trade Center, the highest building in Sri
Lanka, was seriously damaged with almost all windows broken and a
large section of wall collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The twin-tower was opened by Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga three days before the bombing and was regarded as a
sign of the country's economic recovery. The majority of the
investment came from a Singaporean businessman.
</P>
<P>
The bombing could deter other foreign businessmen from
investing in Sri Lanka, which is eager to see more influx of
overseas investment for its development program, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the bombing could foil the government's efforts
to bring in more funds since businessmen could hardly convince
themselves to invest their money in unsafe land.
</P>
<P>
The explosion also dealt a blow to Sri Lanka's tourism
industry, one of the cornerstones in the nation's economy. Luxury
hotel facilities, as well as confidence of tourists, were
destroyed. Many foreign travelers cut short their stay and took
the earliest flights to leave the country Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the blast was a clear signal that the rebels would
by no means lay down their guns and accept the peace package of
the government.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in the north and east is still going on, though
the rebels have been cornered into the jungles after they lost
many of their major positions to the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said it might take months for the World
Trade Center, the Galadari Hotel, the Hilton Hotel, the Bank of
Ceylon and other buildings to clear the tons of rubbles and repair
the damages.
</P>
<P>
As to how long it will take for the country to end the war,
there is still no ready answer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Condemns Record Companies' Monopoly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard today accused multinational record companies of trying to
maintain a monopoly in an attempt to oppose the government's
proposal to scrap import restrictions on compact discs (CD).
</P>
<P>
Australian artists opposed to the government's proposal to
scrap import restrictions on CDs were closely associated with
monopolistic record companies, the prime minister told reporters
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
He said the companies, which were largely foreign owned, were
opposed to his government's proposal because they wanted to
maintain a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
Federal Communications Minister Richard Alston also attacked
major multinational record companies like Sony, EMI, Polygram,
Warner, Universal and BMG for spreading misinformation on the
government's proposal to scrap import restrictions on CDs, the
Australian Associated Press said in a separate story.
</P>
<P>
Local artists have warned that the loosening of import
restrictions on CDs would encourage piracy and lead to loss of
jobs in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Asked why some Australian artists were protesting the proposal
and if only the record companies benefited from the current
arrangements, the prime minister said: "they have close
associations, don't they, with the recording companies."
</P>
<P>
He said the issue was not about protection against piracy and
of copyright, which already existed.
</P>
<P>
It centered on the price of CDs, which would fall by five U.S.
dollars under the proposal, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the Australian public is entitled to know
that this is a contest between the interests of ordinary
Australian consumers and those of large record companies with very
large profits which are trying to maintain an essentially monopoly
position.
</P>
<P>
Alston argued that the music industry's claim of increased CD
piracy was a "red herring" when it came to opening the market to
imported CDs.
</P>
<P>
"Japan imports twice the quantity of English language
recordings as Australia and yet they don't have a piracy problem,
they allow parallel imports," he said.
</P>
<P>
The record companies' threat to withdraw investment in
Australian music talent was hollow, having provided little support
for it except when it suited their commercial interests, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
