<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Introduce Electronic Auto Speed Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
published a document to include automatic speed controls in a list
of measures likely to be introduced to make roads safer.
</P>
<P>
Made public on Wednesday, the document marked a step closer to
taking the futuristic move to enlist the so-called "electronic
roadside brake" as a weapon for reducing road deaths.
</P>
<P>
The proposed system would operate through roadside beacons to
send speed limit information to in-car computers and enforce the
restriction via an engine management device.
</P>
<P>
Officials were quoted as saying by a Times report today that
the system was not a short-term option and more of the kind for
automatic speed control would be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Other measures listed in the document, more of short-term
solutions to road accidents, are further curbs on drink-driving,
better training and improved car design.
</P>
<P>
The government document was out in response to increasing
pressures on authorities for effective traffic-calming schemes and
better protection for the most vulnerable road users, such as
cyclists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
