<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Stronger on US Name Buying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
stronger today, on the back of solid buying by a U.S. bank.
</P>
<P>
The buying was believed to be related to U.S. energy company
GPU Inc. purchase of the Victorian government's PowerNet
electricity transmission network.
</P>
<P>
The network is being purchased by GPU for 2.55 billion
Australian dollars (1.87 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed here at 73.79 U.S. cents, up from
73.51 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Aussie has looked pretty sound with the same guy buying,"
said SBC Warburg Australia foreign exchange executive director
John Radinoff.
</P>
<P>
The currency had started the session with a weaker tone
following a slip in the gold price.
</P>
<P>
"It has been pretty quiet and just softer on the U.S.," said a
trader at a U.S. investment bank. "People are looking to the
Consumer Price Index (CPI) next week and are watching the U.S. in
the meantime."
</P>
<P>
The third quarter CPI report due next Wednesday is expected to
show inflation pressures subside from the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
With economic growth improving, but not enough to make
significant inroads into unemployment, and inflation currently
below the target level, there is ample reason for the Reserve Bank
to cut interest rates, traders held.
</P>
<P>
Australian dollar was at 88.82 from 89.23 against the Japanese
yen, and at 1.2897 from 1.2863 against the German mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
