<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Slide for 6th Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian share market closed
lower for the sixth consecutive session in volatile
futures-related activity.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries rose steadily over the afternoon as
bargain-hunters moved in to close 0.7 points weaker at 2653.0,
just shy of its high of 2653.7.
</P>
<P>
"There were big swings. The market sold down significantly this
morning and there was futures-related selling there," Shaw
Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
"Then there was a pickup of momentum this afternoon and I think
some renewed buying -- some of those prices were just discounted
too far and there was some realization there was value being
presented. And I think there was also in the end some form of
futures-related buying," he said.
</P>
<P>
In New York overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
38.31 points to 8057.98 amid more signs of inflationary pressure
and a disappointing earnings report from Intel.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index rose 13 points to 4370.8
while the all resources fell 13.1 points to 1300.4.
</P>
<P>
BHP shed 27 cents, Rio Tinto eased six and WMC fell 20.1 cents.
</P>
<P>
Among banking stocks, NAB rose 23.4 cents, ANZ added 19, CBA
improved three and Westpac ended steady at 8.66 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 11 points down at 1312.0 with gold
bullion closing at 327.05 U.S. dollars an ounce from 327.00
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 351.38 million shares valued at 1.002
billion Australian dollars (736.47 million U.S. dollars) with
falls outnumbering rises 686 to 427.  
</P>
