<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Press Calls for Sanction Against German Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A group of Bulgarian journalists
and publishers has called on the country's newspapers to join a
sanction against German press group Westdeutsche Allegemeine.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 31 Bulgarian newspapers told a seminar
sponsored by the Bulgarian Association of Newspaper Publishers
that the German group is taking over their country's press market.
</P>
<P>
The outcry is prompted by Westdeutsche Allegemeine's local
acquisition of the "168 Hours" press group's printing house and
Bulgaria's top two daily papers, known as "Labor" and "24 Hours."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Bulgarian publishers said, the German group is
also attempting to control the country's newspaper distribution
system through its own local distribution operation.
</P>
<P>
Now owned by Westdeutsche Allegemeine, "Labor" and "24 Hours"
had a combined circulation of 419,000 as of October 15, equivalent
to 68 percent of the total of Bulgaria's top 10 national dailies.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of the locally-owned Bulgarian newspapers
further alleged that the German group is trying to reduce the
share of profit entitled to local distribution outlets.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, they agreed to submit an appeal to the
Bulgarian parliament and government in protest against what they
called "illegal operations" of German press group in Bulgaria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
