<HEADLINE> ASEAN Economic Ministers Confident of Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 16 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN economic
ministers today expressed their confidence that while the recent
currency situation had affected most members, ASEAN will continue
its high rate of economic growth and remain a dynamic region.
</P>
<P>
They said in a statement at the end of a plenary session here
today that with strong economic fundamentals, abundant investment
opportunities, high savings ratios and consistent application of
sound market-oriented and outward-looking policies, they were
optimistic that ASEAN would overcome the present financial
situation.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the ASEAN finance ministers had discussed the
recent financial situation, the ministers reiterated the support
for the work being carried out by the finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that they will continue to maintain policies at the
individual and regional levels, aimed at ensuring that ASEAN
continued to remain a dynamic and vibrant region for trade and
investments.
</P>
<P>
They also reaffirmed their commitment towards strengthening
ASEAN economic cooperation and in the realization of the targets
set out in various regional economic initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that the ASEAN Vision 2020 charted out the
grouping's strategies for sustained economic and social
development for the advent of the next century.
</P>
<P>
The ministers approved the initial package of offers on the
liberalization of trade services negotiated by ASEAN members since
1996.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the ministers also endorsed the
protocol to implement the initial services package, which is to be
signed at an informal ASEAN summit in Kuala Lumpur in December
this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to adopt an alternative approach to
negotiations in services to ensure the expeditious realization of
free-flow of services in ASEAN by 2020.  
</P>
</TEXT>
