<HEADLINE> Insurgency Makes 300,000 Ugandan People Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Protracted insurgency by the
Rebel Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) has since 1987 made 305,795
people homeless in Uganda's northern district of Gulu Alone,
reported the local press today.
</P>
<P>
Resident district commissioner Peter Odok W'oceng was quoted
as saying that most of these people now live in 20 protected
villages set up since 1996 in the district.
</P>
<P>
About 2,290 metric tons of beans, 4,590 metric tons of maize
flour, 91,740 blankets and 20,530 saucepans are needed for these
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other requirements include medical care, sanitation shelter,
water and education facilities for the children of the displaced,
he said.
</P>
<P>
These figures were the result of a recent survey conducted by
the World Food Program (WFP) and other organisations.
</P>
<P>
LRA was founded in April 1987 by Joseph Kony, a 33-year-old
former catechist in a Catholic parish after he fell out with the
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
The LRA rebels has beein causing disturbance in northern
Uganda, especially Gulu and Kitgum districts, during the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
LRA had more than 2,000 soldiers in the previous years, but
now it only has some 450 fighters as a result of attacks by
government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
