<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Firms Optimistic about Business Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A survey has found that local
companies have strong confidence in Hong Kong's business
environment and are optimistic about their business prospects in
the five years through to 2001.
</P>
<P>
The survey, titled "How Businessmen See 1997 and Beyond", was
conducted by the Federation of Hong Kong Industries during a
period between May and July. 446 firms in the manufacturing,
support services and trading sectors responded.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that the firms expected most of the economic
and social factors affecting the Special Administrative Region
(SAR)'s business environment in 1997 to remain unchanged or even
to be improved. These factors included the availability of land,
labor and technology, the legal system, freedom of information,
labor productivity, infrastructure and trade.
</P>
<P>
Many firms expected an overall improvement in land and labor
availability, access to technology and better infrastructure
during the period from 1997 to 2001. But concern over the legal
system, freedom of information and corruption was expressed by a
significant number of the firms.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the prospects for investment growth, the survey found
that 42 percent expected their investment to increase while 49
percent staying the same in 1997. In the years to 2001, 62 percent
believed their investments would grow while 27 percent staying the
same.
</P>
<P>
As for investment destinations, 70 percent chose China's
interior areas in 1997. Beijing, Shanghai and Dongguan of
Guangdong Province were the most popular investment locations. 41
percent had investments in the SAR and 12 percent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey showed that investment in Hong Kong would
increase substantially in the years to 2001 with 62 percent of the
respondents indicating their intention to invest in the SAR by
the year 2001, 34 percent in China's interior and 12 percent in
other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
As for expectations of turnover and profits, 86 percent of
respondents expected their turnover to increase or remain constant
 in the near future whilst a growth in profits was also
anticipated by over three quarters of the respondents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
