<HEADLINE> Campaign Launched in HK for Film Relics Preservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong Film Archive
collection campaign has been launched here for the preserving of
film heritage, with the public urged to search through their
drawers for any film oldie.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Urban Council, organizer of the campaign,
appealed Wednesday to the public to support this worthy course by
donating or depositing their collections to the care of the Hong
Kong Film Archive.
</P>
<P>
With the support of film organizations, film makers and their
family members, the archive, since its establishment in early
1990s, has managed to collect 2,000 prints and tens of thousands
of film-related materials in the form of scripts, photographs and
magazines, according to the council.
</P>
<P>
The archive has recently obtained more precious artifacts from
the film industry. Among the donors is David Quan, son of the late
kung fu master Kwan Tak-hing, who donated numerous stills,
scripts, costumes and props.
</P>
<P>
But the council wants to tap a rich vein, that is, momentous
movies hoarded by fans for decades.
</P>
<P>
Selected materials from the collection campaign will be
displayed in April 1998 during the 22nd Hong Kong International
Film Festival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
