<HEADLINE> Stable H.K. Wishing to Cooperate With Japanese Firms: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The top official of China's Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) today said Hong Kong
remains stable after its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, told business
leaders here that Hong Kong wishes to cooperate with Japanese
firms to help implement China's economic reform programs.
</P>
<P>
Tung made the remarks while meeting Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman
of Japan's Federation of Economic Organizations, locally known as
Keidanren, and other leaders of the Japanese business community.
</P>
<P>
People's lives in the HKSAR have not been changed since its
return to the motherland, Tung noted, adding that they are
confident of the region's future under the "one country, two
systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
He said the HKSAR has accumulated know-how on corporate
management, and hopes Japanese firms could join in the efforts to
deepen the on-going economic reforms in China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Having large foreign reserves, Hong Kong's currency will keep
pegging with the U.S. dollar, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Currency stability is the key to further prosperity of Hong
Kong's economy, Toyoda said, stressing that it is the most
important factor for the business sector.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived here Wednesday for a three-day visit to Japan, his
first trip to the country as chief executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Tung also met Japanese Finance Minister
Hiroshi Mitsuzuka and the two sides agreed to further strengthen
their relations to forge a "new partnership."
</P>
<P>
During the 30-minute meeting, Mitsuzuka praised Hong Kong's
stable economic and political situation since its handover to
China. 
</P>
