<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Economic Ministers Endorse Agreements to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 16 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN economic
ministers endorsed at their 29th annual meeting here today several
agreements in a move towards liberalizing trade which would
accelerate the achievement of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA).
</P>
<P>
The 29th ASEAN Economic Ministers (AEM) meeting initialed the
protocol on the Notification Procedure (NP) which requires member
countries to inform each other of any modifications in their AFTA
commitments which might impair or nullify any benefit of the
Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme to members.
</P>
<P>
The protocol on the NP, which is expected to be signed early
next year when the ministers meet informally, provides that
members must notify each other at least 60 days in advance to any
changes to the measures with acceptance given if the changes were
made because of a "national emergency".
</P>
<P>
The ministers endorsed the first package of offers under the
Framework Agreement on Services on which negotiations started
early last year on seven priority sectors -- financial services,
tourism, telecommunications, construction, business services, air
and maritime transport.
</P>
<P>
The first package of commitments covering mainly the tourism,
maritime and air transport services is scheduled to be implemented
simultaneously by ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization measures in tourism include visa exemption
and waiver of exit taxes which will further facilitate movements
of travelers and tourists within the region.
</P>
<P>
Air and maritime transport services liberalization would
contribute to the ease of movements of goods and smoothen the flow
of sea and air traffic in the region.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations covering the remaining sectors, namely,
financial services, telecommunications, business services and
construction are scheduled to be completed at the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, new members of the regional grouping -- Laos and
Myanmar also signed the protocol of accession to the remaining
agreements in ASEAN which would include their participation in
AFTA and other economic cooperation arrangements in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar, both admitted into ASEAN in July, have given
assurances that they could meet AFTA commitments in the 10 year
time-frame beginning January 1, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
