<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese State-Owned Enterprises Enhance Competitiveness (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of large
State-owned enterprises in China are joining hands to sharpen their
competitive edge in the market.
</P>
<P>
Chinese economists believe the merger as a new channel for
restructuring the assets of the country's State-owned
enterprises. The new approach has aroused great attention amongst
China's economic circles, and State-owned businesses have emerged
as the centerpiece of the country's economic reform.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China held recently in Beijing, Chinese President Jiang
Zemin called for the establishment of inter-industrial, inter-regional
and multinational consortia based on the market. Economists say
the merging of strong enterprises is of strategic significance in
promoting the establishment of consortia.
</P>
<P>
A petrochemical group consisting of the Jinlin Petrochemical
Corp., the Yangtze Petrochemical Corp., the Yizheng Chemical Fiber
Corp. and the Nanjing Chemical Industrial Co. was formed in Nanjing,
capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, on August 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese State-Owned Enterprises Enhance Competitiveness (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pan Yue, deputy director of the State Property
Administration, said the mergers of large enterprises are "an
important method for restructuring assets and an efficient way
to promote development."
</P>
<P>
The achievements made by highly competitive enterprises which
restructured at an early date verify the feasibility of mergers.
</P>
<P>
The total output of the Zhejiang Medical Joint-Stock Corp. Ltd
rose by 16.5 percent in the first half of this year, compared with
the same period of 1996, with its net profits rising by 57
percent. Three interregional industrial and commercial enterprises
merged to form the company.
</P>
<P>
The Jiuzhitang (Group) Corp. Ltd, a venture formed by two major
pharmaceutical manufacturers in central China, recorded total sales
of 300 million yuan in 1996, a 46 percent rise on 1995.
</P>
<P>
Chinese economists note that
mergers and annexations should adhere to principles of the market
economy. They pointed out that behavior based on the demands
of enterprises themselves and laws governing market operations
generate profits.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that cooperation between strong enterprises
should be in line with local conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese State-Owned Enterprises Enhance Competitiveness (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The TCL Color TV Group in Guangdong Province merged with
the Xinxiang Meile Electronics Group in Henan Province on the
following day.
</P>
<P>
In September, two leading commercial groups in Beijing merged
to become the Beijing Xidan Friendship Group, a venture with
combined assets of 1.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, six major airlines in different localities have
established the Beijing-based Aviation Federation. The China
Eastern Airlines and the China General Airlines are planning to
merge.
</P>
<P>
A common feature of the mergers is that all
the parties involved hope to absorb the advantages of their new
partners and be engaged in mutual promotion efforts.
</P>
<P>
Previously, mergers of State-owned enterprises in China were
based on the concept of "the stronger annexing the weaker", and
were subject to the interference from governments at various
levels. The expanded scale of assets did not necessarily lead to
rising profits.
</P>
<P>
A symposium held in Beijing on October 7 focused on the
restructuring of assets and cooperation between large enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
