<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New ADB Fishery Policy Focuses on Sustainability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
today approved a new fishery policy which will protect the
Asia-Pacific region's rapidly-declining fishery resources.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, the bank said that its new
fishery policy focuses on equity, efficiency and sustainability.
</P>
<P>
"From now on, the ADB will concentrate efforts to protect the
Asian and Pacific region's rapidly declining fishery resources by
helping governments develop policies for long-term sustainable
fishery management and to build up their institutional capability
for resource management," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said it will also encourage more private sector
involvement, especially in production, processing and marketing.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it said, the bank will foster regional cooperation,
especially on matters relating to fish that migrate between
different territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Because of changing circumstances, the new policy represents a
significant change from the bank's 1979 fishery policy which
emphasized production, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the new policy will have an important
implication on the type of fishery projects that the bank approves
for its developing member countries.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that overfishing, excessively large fishing
fleets, a high wastage rate in fish caught and extensive
degradation of coral reefs and mangrove forests are the major
causes of the fish depletion crisis facing the Asian and pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
At present, the bank said, nearly 70 percent of the world's
marine stocks need urgent corrective conservation and management
measures.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that another major problem is the considerable
quantity of fish lost after being caught and before reaching the
consumer.
</P>
<P>
"Up to 20 percent is lost through spoilage due to insufficient
care in handling and transport and poor processing, packaging and
storage," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank added that Asia has the largest fishing fleet which
accounts for 42 percent of the world's gross registered tonnage,
and twice the capacity needed to extract what the oceans can
sustainably produce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
