<HEADLINE> Private Enterprise Helps Salvage State Ones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Xiwang Group, one of the
largest private enterprises in China's inland areas, has helped
turn around more than 40 money-losing State-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu-based group, founded by four Liu brothers and a
major fodder producer in China, produces 2.5 million tons a year,
accounting for 5.4 percent of the national output.
</P>
<P>
One of the State firms salvaged by Xiwang is the Bengbu Fodder
Company in Anhui Province, which had lost 1.5 million yuan
(180,720 U.S. dollars) since 1990.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Xiwang injected technology, trademarks and funds
worth 6 million yuan to form a joint venture with Bengbu. In two
years, the venture turned out pre-tax profits of 12.7 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Another money-losing fodder producer in Wuhan, Hubei Province, was
able to turn out a profit of 740,000 yuan in the first month after
signing a co-op agreement with Xiwang.
</P>
<P>
"The convening of the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China has provided us with new opportunities for further
development," said Liu Yonghao, the Xiwang's general manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
