<HEADLINE> Sassou's Militia Control Pointe-Noire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Forces loyal to Former
Congolese President Sassou Nguesso are reported to have
controlled the oil town Point-Noire in Congo, Kenya's newspaper
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
A diplomat in Pointe-Noire said that pro-Sassou Angolan troops
with tanks had entered the oil-producing town after dawn and
foreign residents there reported looting.
</P>
<P>
"We control the center of the town and we are heading toward
the outskirts where there is some resistance," Isidore Mvouba,
the spokesman of Sassou, claimed.
</P>
<P>
Radio France International quoted the top President Pascal
Lissouba's commander in Point-Noire as saying that he had ordered
his men to surrender, since they lacked the means to defend
themselves against the Angolans.
</P>
<P>
A diplomat reported that Angolan troops have been in the town
since 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Lissouba's forces had been placed on
evacuation standby following the reports of looting in
Pointe-Noire, which is home to 1,600 foreign nationals, most of
them French.
</P>
<P>
Sassou's camp also proclaimed victory in the battle for the
capital. Mvouba told Reuters that they had totally controlled the
city of Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Sassou's militiaa have reached the bridge at Djoue on the south
fringe of Brazzaville and its capture would indicate the whole
capital is now under Sassou's control.
</P>
<P>
Reports say Sassou's militia gained the upper hand in
Brazzaville yesterday, capturing Lissouba's presidential palace.
Earlier they took the airport that had been held by Lissouba's
forces for most of the four-month power struggle.
</P>
<P>
Even though, according to Reuters, Lissouba insisted that he
still regarded himself as the legitimate Head of State.
</P>
<P>
"I can only regard myself as president, since I have not seen
in front of me any successor, elected democratically as I was,"
Lissouba told Radio France in a telephone interview today from an
undisclosed hideout.
</P>
<P>
The whereabouts of Lissouba were not clear.
</P>
<P>
About 800,000 civilian population have fled the capital of
Congo Brazzaville since fighting broke out in June between forces
of Lissouba and those of his rival Sassou. More than 4,000 people
in the city are reported to have been killed.
</P>
<P>
Point-Noire is close to President Lissouba's southern
power basecally and the Angolan enclave of Cabinda, separated from the
main part of former Zaire. It was former French colony's
Atlantic port city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
