<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Fodder Crop Set to Revolutionize Zero-Grazing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A crop scientist at Nairobi
University has developed an improved indigenous variety of the
three-leafed clover plant that will revolutionize the country's
dairy industry, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new clover, developed by Prof. Levi Akundabweni, is a
fast-growing, high yielding, protein-rich and disease/pest-free
fodder crop that will replace protein supplement in zero-grazing
enterprises, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Two small-scale dairy farmers from Githunguri who attended the
unveiling of the new forage recently said the clover would ease
their animal feed problems.
</P>
<P>
"What we have been shown will help us a lot because feeding
cattle in a zero-grazing setup is difficult. If the clover is to
be used with nappier grass, which we thought was the best, it
will be very useful for small-scale enterprises," a farmer said.
</P>
<P>
All parts of the new clover variety, Trifolium quartinanium
which matures in 120 to 130 days, were found to be highly
digestible without any side-effects, said Akundabweni.
</P>
<P>
The purple-flowered stemmy variety of the African Clover which
grows to knee-height "is without any bloat-causing and
cyanogenetic factors," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He added the results of feed trials undertaken in Ethiopia,
where his studies on the plant were initiated, indicated that
Trifolium quartinanium presented "no obvious problems" in cattle.
</P>
<P>
Of some 1,000 strains of the clover plant collected from the
wild, Trifolium quartinanium, with its leafy palatable stems
showed the greatest promise under cultivation as an annual
fodder-bank crop, as well as a soil cover crop in fallow areas.
</P>
<P>
With 10 kilograms of seeds, and under optimal experimental
conditions, the scientist harvested some 10 to 15 tons (fresh
weight) of the plant which upon drying came to six to seven tons
of dry matter per hectare.
</P>
<P>
With this kind of bulk, the professor claimed a farmer would
not only benefit from the nutritional value of the new crop but
also considerably save on the amount of nappier grass with that
he feeds cow every day.
</P>
<P>
High-producing dairy breeds consume up to 15 kilograms of
nappier grass to produce eight liters of milk per day.
</P>
<P>
Even sheep what were fed on dry crop residues such as maize
stover mixed with the clover recorded live weight gains four to
five times more than those fed on the crop residues alone, said
the scientist.
</P>
<P>
In a mixed-farming enterprise, the farmer will also save on
nitrogen fertilizers because this leguminous forage fixes
nitrogen into the soil via its root nodules, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0153 </DOCNO>
