<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches National Health Insurance Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian head of state, General
Sani Abacha on Wednesday launched the country's long-awaited
National Health Insurance Scheme (NHIS) in Abuja, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha reiterated his administration's determination
to make health service affordable and accessible to all
Nigerians. He expressed the hope that the scheme will greatly
accelerate the drive toward "health for all by the year 2000 and
beyond".
</P>
<P>
He pledged the government's commitment to the success of the
scheme, saying that both the federal and state governments will
provide take-off grants for the scheme and that an enabling
decree will be soon promulgated.
</P>
<P>
The head of state promised maximum autonomy for the scheme and
said that private sectors will be encouraged to take part in it.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the NHIS has been in discussion since
1962, however, several attempts to launch it has failed at the
last minute.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, soaring costs of medical services are depriving
more and more people of the accesses to basic health services.
There have been many reports of patients being denied treatment
for failing to pay huge deposits.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, eight states, namely, Borno,
Kaduna, Rivers, Enugu, Kano, Ogun, Plateau, Lagos and Abuja, the
Federal Capital Territory will pilot the NHIS.
</P>
<P>
All civil servants, the police, armed forces and employees of
organizations with more than 10 employees will be involved in the
first phase of the scheme, Health Minister Ihechukwu Madubuike
said at the launching ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to him, workers will have to pay only 45 (about 0.55
U.S. Dollars) to 464 Naira (about 5.66 Dollars) a month to be
covered by the scheme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
