<HEADLINE> Nyerere Urges SADC to Take Part in Africa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzanian
president Julius Nyerere has urged the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to take part in efforts to stop
regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The veteran African politician urged South Africa and other
SADC states to "take serious interest" in allegations that the
army of one of its member countries, Angola, has invaded the
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere arrived in South Africa yesterday for a private visit.
</P>
<P>
Local media today quoted Nyerere as saying in an interview
that SADC, currently chaired by President Nelson Mandela, could
not simply say the Congo conflict was "none of our business".
</P>
<P>
He stressed the region can't just ignore that problem. "We are
all saying that Africa should solve Africa's problems. We can't
solve them by ignoring them."
</P>
<P>
He was responding to a question about what the SADC should do
for reports that Angolan forces had captured Congo's important
city of Pointe-Noire, entering the war on the side of rebel
leader Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
He said citizens of Africa should not stand back and leave the
resolution of conflicts to the Organization of African Unity
only.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere came out strongly in favor of South Africa playing a
more active role in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The African statesman will launch his Dar es Salaam-based
"Mwalimu Nyerere Foundation" in Johannesburg, which aims to
promote peace, unity and people-centered development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to hold talks with Mandela and Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki, and to address members of South African
parliament in Cape Town. 
