<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investors Benefit from Changes in Urbanization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- With the aim of improving the
process of urbanization, China is to adjusting the growth patterns
to provide more opportunities for overseas investors, People's
Daily Overseas Edition has reported.
</P>
<P>
Urban areas are expected to account for 42.6 percent of the
country's total by 2010, a gain of 16.3 percent from current
figures, a recent report on city planning said.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of metropolis and medium-sized cities has
dropped, and cities in regions in west China are required to
greatly improve their infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The number of cities increased to 666 in 1996 with the urban
population accounting for 29 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and
sales volume in cities have accounted for 67.8 percent and 64.4
percent of the country's total respectively.
</P>
<P>
Cities are mainly distributed along China's coastal areas. The
average GDP of large cities is up 86.7 percent over that of
medium-sized cities and 1.5 times the figure for small cities.
</P>
<P>
Major efforts to developing the economy and raising
the GDP of China's cities are necessary to adjust the country's
city distribution, the report said.
</P>
<P>
China's cities, especially those in central and west China,
should improve their infrastructures, such as roads, water and
electricity. The sluggish development of city infrastructures is
due to the shortage of funds, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Now, foreign investors are allowed to invest in the
construction of highways, schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
During the adjustment of urban distribution, more new cities
are appearing, which provide more investment opportunities. Since
the 1980s, China has established special economic zones, bonded
areas and new high-technology development zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
