<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Strongwomen Caught of Unfair Behaviors in Doping Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese strongwomen were
disqualified from the National Games as they were caught of unfair
behaviors in the doping tests, officials of the Games' Organizing
Committee said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the anti-doping rules of the Chinese State Physical
Culture and Sports Commission (CSPCS), the Games' Competition
Department ruled the two cases as positive tests against the two
women lifters.
</P>
<P>
Jin Chunlan of Ning Xia autonomous region was caught on spot on
Wednesday of submitting her prepared tube of urine after the
competitions in the women's 70-kg class where she finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
And Chen Xiaomin of Guangdong province was also caught of
cheating right-handedly last Saturday prior to her competitions in
the 59-kg category.
</P>
<P>
The CSPCS rules stipulate that those who either refuse for or
have unfair behaviors in the doping tests will be considered as
positive tests.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, Jin was stripped of her fifth-place finish while
Chen was prevented from competing in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Weightlifting Association will conduct further
investigation into the cases, and will carry out the punishment
measures against those two athletes in accordance with the rules
of the International Weightlifting Federation, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials said all the gold medalists and record-breakers
are eligible for the doping tests while random tests are being
conducted among those top eight finishers in the on-going National
Games.
</P>
<P>
The CSCPC urged all the participating delegations and members
concerned to further enhance the anti-doping campaign with strict
measures to ensure a successful and clean National Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
