<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Top 30 Business Groups Pushing Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Alarmed by recent corporate
bankruptcies and failures, South Korea's 30 top business groups
are vigorously pushing restructuring and managerial reforms.
</P>
<P>
The efforts, said the Fair Trade Commission (FTC), are focused
on disposal of unprofitable units, intersubsidiary mergers, real
estate sell-offs, and entry into state-of-the-art and high
value-added fields.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, management reforms undertaken by these groups
include freezing wages, streamlining organizations, improving
productivity and cutting costs, the FTC said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The biggest conglomerates, said an FTC official, "are waking up
to the need to improve their corporate health, particularly in
this rapidly changing business environment at home and abroad."
</P>
<P>
The content of managerial reforms differs, depending on the
size of the conglomerate, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Top 30 Business Groups Pushing Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Alarmed by recent corporate
bankruptcies and failures, South Korea's 30 top business groups
are vigorously pushing restructuring and managerial reforms.
</P>
<P>
The efforts, said the Fair Trade Commission (FTC), are focused
on disposal of unprofitable units, intersubsidiary mergers, real
estate sell-offs, and entry into state-of-the-art and high
value-added fields.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, management reforms undertaken by these groups
include freezing wages, streamlining organizations, improving
productivity and cutting costs, the FTC said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The biggest conglomerates, said an FTC official, "are waking up
to the need to improve their corporate health, particularly in
this rapidly changing business environment at home and abroad."
</P>
<P>
The content of managerial reforms differs, depending on the
size of the conglomerate, he said.
</P>
<P>
The top 15 conglomerates, while paying attention to disposal of
unprofitable business lines, cost reduction and other conventional
restructuring methods, tend to give top priority to expansion into
state-of-the-art and high value-added fields, such as
semiconductors, telecommunications and aerospace.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the "minor" groups, ranked between 16th and 30th
in the corporate hierarchy, are trying to improve their financial
structure through various cost reduction measures and
concentrating investments in a few key strategic fields.
</P>
<P>
The FTC report said the Hyundai Group will increase technology
investments by 10 percent and reduce costs by 10 percent annually,
while the Samsung Group will scale down its planned investments
from 70 trillion won (about 77.8 billion U.S. dollars) to 40
trillion won (44.4 billion dollars) by 2000 and cut costs by 30
percent over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The LG Group's restructuring drive calls for pumping about 23
trillion won (25.6 billion dollars) into the telecom sector and
production of next-generation chips by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Daewoo Group intends to suspend acquisition of new real
estate, while the Sunkyong Group has merged seven subsidiaries and
is planning to liquidate two loss-making units.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing restructuring moves is likely to help boost the
slow economy as well as the competitivenesses of the conglomerates
in the second half of 1998, said the FTC report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing to Expand Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Michael Zimmerman, president of
Boeing China Inc., expressed confidence recently that his company
would be China's partner in the country's next major aircraft
manufacturing project.
</P>
<P>
Boeing suffered two setbacks in China. In the 1980s, Boeing
lost out to McDonnell Douglas Corp. in the competition for China's
trunk line aircraft project, and in the 1990s it lost a bid for
China's 100-seat aircraft plan to the European manufacturer of the
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the failures, Boeing has never lost its confidence
in the Chinese market," Zimmerman said. Boeing, which merged last
year with McDonnell Douglas, will carry out the contracts the two
companies had signed with China and attempt to increase market
share.
</P>
<P>
Zimmerman said Boeing plans to bring more technology, personnel
resources and funds into China, the second largest aviation
market in the world.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua prior to Chinese President Jiang
Zemin's visit to the United States, Zimmerman said that Boeing has
been working on Sino-US relations for years, including launching a
grassroots movement to persuade U.S. legislators to grant China
the most-favored-nation trade status.
</P>
<P>
Zimmerman said good political ties will spur two-way trade, and
that setbacks and difficulties in bilateral relations would
adversely affect economic cooperation. He said Sino-U.S. ties
appear to be improving after many ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang's U.S. visit will be important for the
development of political and economic ties between the two
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
To show Boeing's confidence in China, the firm made its first
direct investment in China this year when it poured 11 million
U.S. dollars into an aircraft maintenance joint venture in Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
"This is Boeing's first step of direct investment in China,"
said Jiande Chen, director of public affairs of Boeing China. "The
step will be larger in the future."
</P>
<P>
Boeing signed its first contracts with China for processing
aircraft components in the early 1970s. Now, more than 2,000
Boeing aircraft are equipped with parts built in
China, including vertical fins, horizontal stabilizers and
trailing edge ribs for the Boeing 737, as well as cargo doors for
the 757.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in 1998, Boeing will cooperate with aircraft
manufacturers in Xi'an, Shenyang and Shanghai to produce more
aircraft parts.
</P>
<P>
"The quality of Chinese products is high and delivery is on
time," Zimmerman said, adding that the good reputation helped
Boeing's partners in China win the opportunity to take part in the
design and manufacture of parts for the next-generation
737. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
