<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Ambassador to Israel Returns Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadian ambassador to
Israel David Berger has returned to his post in Tel Aviv after
Israel promised that Israeli intelligence agents would stop
using forged Canadian passports, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Canada recalled Berger on October 4 in protest against the
botched Mossad (Israeli intelligence agency) operation in Amman
in which two Israeli agents, carrying false Canadian passports,
attempted to kill Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) political
leader Kahled Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Ben-Gurion airport after his arrival
Wednesday, Berger said that only after his government had
considered the Mashaal affair closely and got promise from
Israel, he was sent back to his post.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that he was satisfied with the assurance from
Israel and he was ready to return to business as usual.
</P>
<P>
Berger's return was attributed by the Canadian Embassy in Tel
Aviv to Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy's assurance that
"steps will be taken to prevent more incidents like the one in
Jordan in the future."
</P>
<P>
Levy's efforts to repair the damage done to the normally
cordial links with Canada began the day after Berger's
departure. He telephoned his Canadian counterpart Lloyd Axworthy
immediately after the incident.
</P>
<P>
Levy also sent a letter to Axworthy, in which he reiterated
his deep regret that the safety of Canadians traveling aboard
may have been compromised by the Mossad action.
</P>
<P>
He assured Axworthy that Israel fully appreciates "the
concern" of the Canadian government and people, saying the
Israeli authorities have taken steps to prevent the recurrence of
such incidents.
</P>
<P>
After Axworthy received Levy's letter last Friday, he
immediately announced that Ambassador David Berger would be sent
back to his post in Tel Aviv. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
