<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Experts Expect Fast Growth in the Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Oil experts at the 15th World
Petroleum Congress (WPC) forecast flat oil prices in real terms
for the next 15 years, and they hope to see oil demand growing to
nearly 100 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
In the speech titled "Competitive Imperatives and Critical
Challenges for the Global Oil Industry", Kenneth T. Derr, chairman
of the board and chief executive officer of Chevron Corporation,
noted that "the world is sharing an enormous anticipation for oil
growth".
</P>
<P>
He said that major oil growth is expected worldwide, mainly in
Canada and Kuwait, at Bombai High and in Bakersfield, at Kutubu
and Malongo, around the Persian Gulf and in the Pearl River Mouth
Basin.
</P>
<P>
According to the senior oil official, Venezuela wants to double
its oil production by 2006. Statoil wants to add 200,000 barrels
per day outside Norway by 2005.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, Petrobras seeks a 50 percent rise in crude
production and Ecopetrol aims to boost production to one million
barrels per day. Also by 2000, LUK oil plans to invest in new
production at twice today's spending level. Meanwhile, BP wants to
grow production 60 percent in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
China has new deals with Kazakhstan, Venezuela and Iraq -- plus
an alliance with Agip, he acknowledged. They are also looking for
onshore growth at home through ventures like the deep exploration
project with Chevron at the Shengli Oilfield in east China.
</P>
<P>
He added that it is right to call China "a new star on the
world oil stage."
</P>
<P>
More than anything else, the world oil industry is more driven,
because it is standing on the threshold of a great expansion, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
