<HEADLINE> Badminton Youngesters Urged to Treasure Sports Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Former badminton king Zhao
Jianhua Wednesday appealed to the young stars to treasure their
sports career by taking every match seriously both at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, a super star in the late 1980s, paced his native Jiangsu
province to the team title at the ongoing Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
The former world champion had been studying in a college and
working as a part-time coach in Singapore after retiring in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He was called up by Jiangsu province to take part in the Eighth
National Games, as a spiritual pillar other than a top shuttler in
the team, which was mainly composed of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old competed in the men's doubles and team events.
Although he was exhausted and failed to make the finals in
doubles, the vetaran had displayed his never-say-loss nerves in
the fifth-place elimination match.
</P>
<P>
"Although I'm tired and not battling for the title, I treasure
the oppoturnity," he said. "This might be the last chance for me
to compete in the Games as a player."
</P>
<P>
"For a shuttler, his sports career is very short. Please work
hard when you are still young or you would regret for the rest of
your life," he warned the young shuttlers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
