<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM Howard Defends Australia's Asia Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard defended today his government's Asia-first policy and
described the Asia-only policy pursued by the former government as
misplaced and shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
Responding to criticism by Melbourne leading businessman Lloyd
Williams of his government's Asia policy, the prime minister said
Williams was wrong.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Williams said he wished Paul Keating were still
prime minister as he accused the government of being out of step
in its attitude to Asia.
</P>
<P>
"His claim that we're out of step with Asia is totally wrong,"
Howard was quoted by the Australian Associated Press as telling
journalists in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"What I think the events in Asia of the last few weeks have
demonstrated is that the Asia-only policy followed by the former
government was misplaced and shortsighted," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was clearly referring to the financial
crisis going on in some Southeast Asian countries, including
Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"We are following an Asia-first policy, we're not following an
Asia-only policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Criticism I had of the Keating government's approach to Asia
policy is that it put all of its economic and political eggs in
the Asian basket instead of recognizing the importance of
understanding that we live in a world of different parts and we
have to have economic and political linkages with all parts of the
globe," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Williams was talking to media today after the annual meeting of
a construction company in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"I do think Paul Keating had a wonderful vision. I only wish
Paul Keating was here because he would have got rid of the Hanson
factor," Williams said.
</P>
<P>
The Howard government was accused of being late in launching
counterattacks against the anti-Asian immigration views
represented by independent MP Pauline Hanson and her One Nation
Party.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the younger conservatives realize Australia needs to
be embracing Asia. They (the government) have got to get to the
stage of recognizing where their markets are," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asia is Australia's largest overseas market, accounting for
about 60 percent of its total export.  
</P>
</TEXT>
