<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Northwest Border Area Benefits from Opening-up Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 20,000 foreign
traders had visited a frontier market at the Horgas Port and
bought various goods worth 170 million yuan in the first half of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The port, located in the Yili Prefecture of northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region bordering Kazakhstan, has become
a showcase of cross-border trade between China and Central Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Before China opened its border area in
1992, the prefecture's trade relations with the outside were
limited. Now it boasts more than 30 million U.S. dollars annually
in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The market has been expanded to 1,500 stands which can
accommodate 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Traders from Zhejiang Province, east China, sell textile
products worth 200 U.S. dollars annually, along with 1 billion
yuan of household electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
Booming foreign trade has in turn promoted local economic
growth. The Border Economic Cooperation Zone, set up in
1992, has accounted for 36 million U.S. dollars in exports and
imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Asian Countries Plan Transnational Pipeline Project (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ott Victor Logancsvich, Russian vice-minister of fuel and
energy, told local media Wednesday at the WPC that Russia and
China have spent three years on a feasibility study of two
pipelines connecting the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Chengwu, chief representative of the China
National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) in Moscow, one project is to
link the natural gas fields in Russia's Irkutsk with Rizhao of
east China's Shangdong Province, and will extend to the Republic
of Korea (ROK) and Japan at its final stage.
</P>
<P>
The other pipeline, running from West Siberia to China's
Shanghai via the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, is slated to
ease the energy bottleneck in the booming east and southeast areas
of China.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the two projects will pump a maximum of 5
percent of Russia's gas output to the target countries, said one
gas expert.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, Russia and ROK also held bilateral talks
amid Sino-Russian negotiations and reached initial agreements on
sharing gas transmitted from Mongolia and China.
</P>
<P>
Japanese energy authorities and petroleum corporations also
applied to China and Russia to join the program.
</P>
<P>
The whole project, with a combined truck pipeline length of
3,500 kilometers, could cost 8-10 billion U.S. dollars, according
to Chen Jiqing, director of CNPC's Pipeline Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The whole project could take 8-10 years for construction. Upon
completion, the peak transporting capacity could reach 20 billion
cubic meters annually, Chen said, and the pipelines are designed
to last 20 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Annual gas demand worldwide should reach 2.5 trillion cubic
meters by the year 2000 and 3 trillion cubic meters by 2010,
compared to 2.2 trillion cubic meters in 1995, according to
official statistics released at the conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
