<HEADLINE> Northeast Asian Countries Plan Transnational Pipeline Project (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Countries in northeast Asia are
planning to build several transnational pipeline projects linking
the natural gas-rich Russia with Mongolia, China, the Republic of
Korea and Japan, according to sources at the 15th World Petroleum
Congress (WPC) here.
</P>
<P>
According to Gao Tangui, chief engineer of the China Oil and
Gas Pipeline Bureau, Russia's East Siberia, the Far East region
and Sakhalin (Kuye Island) boast abundant natural gas
resources. Experts estimated reserves in the region at 56 trillion
cubic meters, of which 57 percent is in East Siberia and 19
percent in its Far East region.
</P>
<P>
According to a development program mapped out by a Russian
energy research institute, the gas export in the above two regions
could hit 49 billion cubic meters by 2010, becoming a steady gas
supplier for Northeast Asia countries.
</P>
<P>
Economists around the world shared the view that the northeast
Asian countries could provide an economic boost to the global
economy. The rising energy demand and high pressure from
environmentalists may force more countries to increase the use of
clean, energy-efficient gas in their energy consumption and
chemical development.
</P>
<P>
Some experts have predicted that the gas demand in China, Japan
and the Republic of Korea may hit 100 to 150 billion cubic meters
between the year 2000 and 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
