<HEADLINE> Zambia May Have Below Normal Rainfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 16 (Xinhua)-- Zambia may have a generally
below normal rainfall, according to the latest forecast from the
country's Meteorological Department.
</P>
<P>
Near normal rainfall is expected over Northwestern, Luapula
and Northern provinces while Copperbelt, Lusaka, Eastern and some
southern parts of Western province will face long spells of rain
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Statistical models of the department indicate that Luapula,
Lusaka and Western provinces will start off with near normal
rainfall during the months of November and December as the rest
of the country continue experiencing little rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The severe deficit of the rainfall will be felt as the season
gets along in those areas with below normal rainfall.
</P>
<P>
Rain and weather patterns for the 1997/98 season have greatly
been affected world wide by the powerful El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
El Nino could either cause floods, heavy rainfall, or extreme
drought in different parts of the world. 
</P>
