<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-meter Water Depth Drilling Technology Announced at WPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The French petroleum engineers
has launched a new-generation of drilling technology at the
2,000-meter-deep sea bottom, and thus lay the foundation for the
technical progress in offshore oil industry in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the French Association of
Professional Petroleum Technicians, the drilling technology,
nicknamed "slim hole," is developed jointly by Forasol-Foramer
Corporation and Elf, one of the global oil producers.
</P>
<P>
By using the technology, offshore oil producers can made a
3,000-meter drilling well in water depth of 2,000 meters or beyond
within 45 days, and can reduce the costs by 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
The "Slim Hole" is expected to overcome the technical
challenges, such as kick detection, kick control, mechanical
behavior of drill-string and rheological behavior of the mud, in
the present offshore oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Industrial analysts said that the technology will be put into
commercial development in oilfield of 2,000-meter water depth by
the year 2000, and will be available to offshore oil projects
2,500 meters below the sea level in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The drilling well built by Petrobras, the state-owned oil
company of Brazil, in Campos Basin this year now keeps the water
depth record of 1,709 meters.
</P>
<P>
Dirk van der Meer, president of WPC, said that the breakthrough
in drilling technology for the deeper water exploration will
expand the width and depth of offshore development of global oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
So far the output of offshore oil accounts for about one third
of the total of the global oil industry. The proportion will
further expand in the next century, according to the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
