<HEADLINE> Kenya Earns $246M from Coffee Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has sold coffee worth 15
billion Shillings (246 million U.S. Dollars) since the beginning
of the 1996/97 crop year, according to the latest Coffee Board of
Kenya (CBK) marketing report available here today.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the 1995/95 crop year, the country recorded a 10
percent increase in the value of coffee sold, but a decline of
24.7 percent in the volume.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.17 million bags of coffee (50 kilograms per bag)
were sold during the 1996/97 crop year, down from 1.55 million
bags sold in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
At the central auction held every Tuesday here, the average
price for per bag stood at 207.78 Dollars, a 25.1 percent rise
compared to the average price of 117.25 Dollars for the 1995/96
crop year.
</P>
<P>
Germany topped the list of importers with 465,383 bags valued
at 6.1 billion Shillings (100 million Dollars), followed by
Sweden, Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Finland, Belgium, Italy, Spain, France and Saudi Arabia are
also the main buyers of Kenya coffee, most of them Arabica type.
</P>
<P>
The CBK now projects increased production from the 1997/98
crop with more land being put under coffee in the Rift Valley in
this east African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
