<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Roman Catholics in China Inreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Fu Tieshan, Vice-Chairman
of the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association, told Xinhua recently
that there are now 4 million Catholics including 1,200 priests in China.
</P>
<P>
They are active in the country, involved in various activities like
disaster relief work, social services, and international religious
events, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
The 66-year-old bishop said that Catholicism has entered its
golden age in China as a result of the religious policy of the
Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
"The CPC has always attached great importance to protecting and
respecting the freedom in religious beliefs. Since the Third
Plenary Session of the 11th CPC Central Committee in 1978, the
religious policy has had satisfactory results," Fu said.
</P>
<P>
"Communists believe in Marxism and Leninism, we Catholics
believe in God. Differences in beliefs do not hinder our
co-operation and mutual respect," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Fu graduated from a Beijing Catholic college in 1941, and he
has served as bishop of the Beijing parish since 1979.
</P>
<P>
He said that 1,700 people are studying to become priests in 31
monasteries across the country. China now has 115 parishes, 40 of
which have convents with a total of 2,000 nuns.
</P>
<P>
His association is calling on the Catholics in China to
love the country and contribute to it, and to safeguard China's
sovereignty and national unity, he said, adding religions in
China will have an even brighter future after the 15th CPC National
Congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
