<HEADLINE> UK Consortium to Build Container Depot in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Some leading UK-based companies
have formed a consortium recently to construct with private
investment a new container terminal near Chittagong seaport, the
economy lifeline of Bangladesh, informed sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Port Ventures Limited (PVL), the company set up by the
consortium, has already selected a suitable site at the mouth of
river Karnaphuli to build the terminal with an estimated cost of
300 to 350 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first private sector container-handling port
in Bangladesh, which is designed with a handling capacity of 0.5
million TEU containers annually by 2010, said a senior official of
the PVL.
</P>
<P>
TEU is abbreviated from tweentyfoot equivalent unit that is a
standard container.
</P>
<P>
He said the feasibility study is expected to be completed by
the end of December this year. PVL will then make a cost
evaluation of the project in order to confirm the private sector
finance and relevant concession from the government for proposal.
</P>
<P>
The detailed engineering design and development would be
completed in 1998 and the construction is expected to commence
early 1999, said the official, adding that the construction of the
project would be completed by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
By the year of 2005, the new port's capacity will stand at
200,000 to 250,000 TEUs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
