<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier, Exxon CEO Discuss Petrochemical Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Revitalizing China's
petrochemical industry is an important step in further opening up
the country's economy, Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Lee R. Raymond, chairman and chief executive
officer of Exxon, the U.S. petroleum giant, Wu said the demand for
petrochemical products is on the rise in China. Petrochemical
industry will be one of China's economic pillars because of the
broad prospects for its development.
</P>
<P>
Wu praised Exxon's cooperation with the country's enterprises,
including China Petrochemical Corporation (Sinopec).
</P>
<P>
On October 13, Sinopec signed an agreement with Exxon and
Aramco of Saudi Arabia for a joint feasibility study for a
refinery and petrochemical complex in east China's coastal
province of Fujian which will involve a total investment of three
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
After completing the project, Fujian will become a
10-million-ton refinery center for processing high-sulphur crude
oil with an annual capacity of manufacturing 600,000 tons of
ethylene.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the agreement indicates bilateral cooperation has made
major strides. Exchanges and cooperation between Chinese and
U.S. enterprises are expanding, he said, which helps improve
governmental relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin will soon pay a state visit to
the U.S. at the invitation of his U.S. counterpart, Bill Clinton,
who will visit China next year.
</P>
<P>
"This high-level exchange of visits will serve to further
promote the understanding of the two peoples, and to enhance the
economic cooperation and development of the two nations," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Raymond said his company is determined to
set up a long-term cooperative relationship with Chinese
enterprises and is confident of making such cooperation successful.
</P>
<P>
Exxon will join Sinopec to set up two more joint ventures in
China: one for lubricant additives in Jinzhou, a city in
northeastern China's Liaoning Province, and the other for
petrochemical carbon 5 resin in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
These joint ventures will begin this year.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, vice-minister of the State Planning Commission,
and some noted figures in China's petroleum sector also were
present at today's meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
