<HEADLINE> Rupee Adjustment to Boost Exports: Pak PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif said here today that the eight percent adjustment in
rupee value would boost exports and improve the overall economic
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Our exports will increase and we will be able to compete in
the international markets," Sharif told reporters this morning at
the Islamabad Airport prior to his departure for Turkmenistan on a
day-long visit.
</P>
<P>
The State Bank of Pakistan on Wednesday adjusted the
dollar-rupee (buying) rate by 8.71 percent from 40.52 rupees to a
U.S. dollar to 44.05 rupees.
</P>
<P>
"It is a timely decision which will benefit the country,"
Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
To a question, Sharif said that the government had given wheat
farmers a much better per acre price for their crop than before to
increase the production.
</P>
<P>
The government is also expecting a good harvest of cotton, rice
and sugarcane, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had decided to extend 90 billion rupees
(about 2.05 billion U.S. dollars) credit to farmers.
</P>
<P>
"This is a bold step which will provide a lot of incentives to
our farmers," he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to a another question, Sharif said that the Swiss
government had frozen the bank accounts of former Pakistani prime
minister Benazir Bhutto and her relatives after the Pakistani
government provided solid evidences.
</P>
<P>
This is for the first time in the history of Pakistan that such
a step has been taken, said Sharif, adding that all the looted
money will be brought back to the national exchequer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharif said the revenue collection targets set by
the Central Board of Revenue had been achieved during the first
quarter of current fiscal year starting from July 1, 1997.
</P>
