<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Farm Workers Get 40 Percent Wage Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's farm workers have
been awarded a 40 percent wage increase and more leave days after
an accord reached yesterday between the General Agriculture and
Plantation Workers' Union and the Agricultural Labor Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The new wages range from 503 Zimbabwe Dollars (40 U.S.
Dollars) a month to 716 Zimbabwe Dollars (57 Dollars), depending
on grade.
</P>
<P>
A 40 percent increase across the board was agreed along with
an increase in leave days from 12 working days to 15 a year. The
agreement is with effect from September 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean farm workers have been holding the countrywide
strike in the past one month, demanding an increase of 135
percent wage. The strike, first ever by farm workers, started in
the enterprise farming area before it spread to other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
During the strike, the destruction of vehicles, tobacco seed
beds and buildings were reported in some areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
