<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Calls for Universal Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral called on Wednesday for a universal extradition
treaty and suggested that an internationally acceptable code of
conduct for governments should be evolved to check various crimes
around the world, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The bilateral extradition treaties may not work in the ongoing
globalization of crimes," Gujral told the 66th annual general
assembly session of the International Criminal Police Organization
(Interpol) which opened here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stated that though a universal extradition
treaty could form part of the United Nations agenda, some
international conventions will have to be built to save the
countries from the agonizing negotiations in seeking the
extradition of wanted criminals.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the new forms of corruption taking place at the
international level, Gujral said that money-laundering and other
inter-related crimes in drug-trafficking and arms smuggling had
led to a kind of race between the law-breakers and law enforcing
agencies.
</P>
<P>
White-collared crimes can only be controlled by greater
cooperation among the nations in high-tech crime detection and
speedy communication, Gujral noted.
</P>
<P>
The week-long general assembly session of the Interpol, hosted
by India for the first time, is being attended by over 500
delegates, including interior ministers and top police officers
and investigators from 177 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
