<BODY>
<HEADLINE> None in China Punished Because of Religious Belief: White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The punishment of criminals by
China's judicial organs has nothing to do with religious belief,
and no one in China is punished because of his or her religious
belief, an official white paper said today.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper entitled "Freedom of Religious Belief in China"
was issued today by the Information Office of the State Council,
said that since the 1980s, some pernicious organizations have
sprung up in certain areas of China, which are engaged in illegal
and even criminal activities under the religious signboard.
</P>
<P>
Some of the heads of these pseudo-religions distort religious
doctrines, create heresies, deceive the masses, refuse to obey the
State's laws and decrees, and incite people to overthrow the
government. Some pretend to be supernatural beings, and have
killed or injured people; others organize promiscuity, or defraud
people of money or property. They are a serious danger to the
normal life and productive activities of the people, according to
the white paper.
</P>
<P>
"The broad masses of the people and personages of the religious
circles detest this phenomenon," the white paper said.
</P>
<P>
In order to safeguard the public interest and the sanctity of
the law, and to better protect the people's right to freedom of
religious belief and normal religious activities, China's judicial
organs punish law-breakers and criminals who severely endanger the
society and the public interest in accordance with the law, said
the white paper.
</P>
<P>
The punishment of criminals by China's judicial organs has
nothing to do with religious belief, and no one in China is
punished because of his or her religious belief.
</P>
<P>
"No country that practices the rule of law in the world today
would tolerate illegal and criminal activities being carried out
under the banner of religion," the white paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
