<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues White Paper on Freedom of Religious Belief (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Information Office of the
State Council today issued a White Paper on Freedom of Religious
Belief in China, which indicates with large quantities of facts
that the freedom of religious belief of the Chinese people has
been well respected and protected since the founding of the
People's Republic of China in 1949, particularly in the recent two
decades following the implementation of the reform and opening-up
policies.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, with more than 10,000 Chinese characters,
consists of five parts: The Present Conditions of Religion in
China, Legal Protection of the Freedom of Religious Belief,
Judicial and Administrative Guarantees and Supervision of the
Freedom of Religious Belief, Support for Independence and
Initiative in Management of Religious Affairs, and Protection of
the Right to Freedom of Religious Belief for Ethnic Minorities.
</P>
<P>
According to the white paper, China is a country with a great
diversity of religious beliefs. The main religions are Buddhism,
Taoism, Islam, Catholicism and Protestantism. Citizens of China
may freely choose and express their religious beliefs, and make
clear their religious affiliations.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are over 100 million followers of
various religious faiths, more than 85,000 sites for religious
activities, and over 3,000 religious organizations throughout
China. In addition, there are 74 religious schools and colleges
run by religious organizations for training clerical personnel.
</P>
<P>
Among the 300,000 clergy in China, there are some 200,000
Buddhist monks and nuns, more than 25,000 Taoist priests and nuns,
over 40,000 Imams and Akhunds, 4,000 clergy of Catholicism, and
more than 18,000 clergy of Protestantism, the white paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues White Paper on Freedom of Religious Belief (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Religious organizations in China run their own affairs
independently and set up religious schools, publish religious
classics and periodicals, and run social services according to
their own needs. As in many other countries, China practices the
principle of separating religion from education; religion is not a
subject taught in schools of the popular education in China,
although some institutions of higher learning and research
institutes do teach or conduct research into religion, the white
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The various religious schools and institutes set up by the
different religious organizations teach religious knowledge in
line with their own needs.
</P>
<P>
All normal clerical activities conducted by the clergy and all
normal religious activities held either at sites for religious
activities or in believers' own homes in accordance with usual
religious practices are protected by law as the affairs of
religious bodies and believers themselves.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that in the course of the country's long
history, the various religions in China have become part of the
traditional Chinese thinking and culture. It is traditional for
Chinese religious believers to love their country and religions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government supports and encourages the religious
circles to unite the religious believers to actively participate
in the construction of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues White Paper on Freedom of Religious Belief (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In China, all religions have equal status and coexist in
tranquillity. Religious disputes are unknown in China. Religious
believers and nonbelievers respect each other, are united and have
a harmonious relationship.
</P>
<P>
This shows, on the one hand, the influence of traditional
Chinese compatibility and tolerance, and, on the other, the fact
that since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949
the Chinese government has formulated and carried out the policy
of freedom of religious belief and established a
politico-religious relationship that conforms to China's national
conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to the white paper, Chinese citizens' right to the
freedom of religious belief is protected by the Constitution and
laws.
</P>
<P>
In the Constitution of the People's Republic of China, freedom
of religious belief is a basic right enjoyed by all citizens.
Article 36 of the Constitution stipulates, "Citizens of the
People's Republic of China enjoy freedom of religious belief." It
also goes on to say, "No State organ, public organization or
individual may compel citizens to believe in, or not to believe
in, any religion; nor may they discriminate against citizens who
believe in, or do not believe in, any religion." Again, "the State
protects normal religious activities," and "No one may make use of
religion to engage in activities that disrupt public order, impair
the health of citizens or interfere with the educational system of
the State." In addition, "Religious bodies and religious affairs
are not subject to any foreign domination."
</P>
<P>
China's Law on National Regional Autonomy, General Principles
of the Civil Law, Education Law, Labor Law, Compulsory Education
Law, Electoral Law of the People's Congresses, Organic Law of the
Villagers' Committees, Advertisement Law, and other laws stipulate
that all citizens, regardless of their religious beliefs, have the
right to vote and stand for election; the legitimate property of
religious bodies is subject to legal protection; education is
separate from religion, and all citizens, regardless of their
religious beliefs, enjoy equal educational opportunities in
accordance with the law; the people of all ethnic groups should
respect each other's languages, customs and habits, and religious
beliefs; citizens shall not be discriminated against in terms of
employment because of different religious beliefs; and no
advertisements or trade marks shall include discriminatory
contents against any ethnic group or religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ma Junren Clouds Legendary Ego in National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Ma Junren, a controversial
coach with world record-breaking protegees years ago, has a
legendary model to follow at the on-going Eighth National Games --
Ma Junren himself.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, Ma orchestrated his "Ma's Family" to stun the
world with three world records in Beijing, vaulting China to an
athletics giant overnight.
</P>
<P>
Such a happy hunting ground is unlikely to be resurrected this
time in Shanghai where he himself was echoing a down-noted message
about his newly-recruited disciples as the track competitions
which will unveil on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"No miracle will be created before the 2000 Olympic Games," Ma
said, joking that "I am not in charge of coaching the athletes.
I'm only a chef and driver here."
</P>
<P>
Last November, he gave up full-time coaching due to poor
health. But nobody is to believe his funny words except those
dumb fools.
</P>
<P>
Admist smoking screens, the mysterious coach eventually shew up
at the Shanghai Stadium along with his 31 proteges and four
assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
Hiding away from the star-rated hotel designated by the Games's
Organizing Committee, Ma himself booked a small and unknown hotel
in a corner of Shanghai instead, signalling to the press that he
has be fed up with the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Wang Junxia, Qu Yunxia and Liu Dong whipped up an
Oriental storm in the World Athletics Championships in Stuttgart
by winning three gold medals in the middle and long-distances
finals.
</P>
<P>
One year later, the Ma's Family created a more surprising feat
in the Seventh National Games, stomping three world records, and
made a clean sweep of the top four places in the Spain marathon.
</P>
<P>
The gust of the Ma's protegees made the world aghast as the
track competitions became meaningless to their opponents of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Without any doubt, the aurae of the Ma dynasty will last for one
decade at least.
</P>
<P>
But the world is like the pot mixed with joy and sorrow. When
all a-growing and a-blowing, Ma Junren was plunged into his worst
moments after Wang Junxia and Qu Yunxia shedded their last shines
under his charge in the Hiroshima Asian Games in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Wang, his most glittering star disciple and Jesse Owens Award
winner, broke away from Ma Junren with Liu Dong, declaring the
break-down the Ma's Family as the coach was reportedly refused to
give them the Mercedes Benz cars, which they won as gifts from the
Stuttgart Worlds. The two found a new coach Mao Dezhen.
</P>
<P>
Ma lamented that Wang and Liu had put a brake upon his efforts
to train younger runners. "They should have stayed in the camp
for themselves and for the younger runners as well, but they
choosed to go away. There was nothing I could do."
</P>
<P>
Misfortunes knocked ajar the door of coach Ma Junren further as
he was hospitalized for months after a car accident and an ailment
to his kidneys.
</P>
<P>
However, Ma remains as a man of stamina. Against the doubts
upon his prospect, he began to recamp the Ma Family with many a
teenage runners.
</P>
<P>
"I am setting my sights upon the 2000 Olympic Games and I'm
confident that my girls will be good enough to create miracles in
Sydney."
</P>
<P>
To prepare for the National Games, Ma led his 31 disciples to
the Duoba Center in Qinghai province for altitude trainning, the
ninth time he visited the camp before major competitions.
</P>
<P>
He shut his door closed all the time to the reporters as his
proteges trained from early morning to late night.
</P>
<P>
On February 26, the 52-year-old coach toured to Hong Kong for
the first race for his athletes after the 1994 Asian Games, saying
"my health is only Ok."
</P>
<P>
His new recruits Yin Lili and Wang Xiaoxia won the women's King
of the Road race in Hong Kong as expected.
</P>
<P>
Coach Ma is full of confidence that a new generation of long
distance runners is maturing in China as other provinces are
learning his training tactics.
</P>
<P>
"China will cherish its new champions at the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney," he vowed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
