<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Revenue Short of Target in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The revenue collection of the
Bangladesh government during the first quarter of the 1997-98
fiscal year stood at 30.78 billion taka (about 690 million U.S.
dollars), 2.2 billion taka (about 50 million dollars) behind the
target.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Board of Revenue (NBR), the
collection for the period of July to September was, however, up by
12.27 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In September, 98.02 percent of the target was achieved with a
shortfall of 232 million taka (about 5.27 million dollars) while
in July and August, only 90.97 percent of the target was
fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Although the NBR managed to stem a drastic downward slide
during the quarter, it received a big blow when importers of
reconditioned cars took it to the court on a series of writs
challenging the imposition of duties, a senior NBR official said.
</P>
<P>
It clipped at least 2 billion taka (about 45 million dollars)
from the government's coffers, keeping the collection sluggish,
and this may strain the beleaguered NBR to achieve its projected
150 billion taka (about 3.4 billion dollars) collection for the
year, claimed the NBR official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
