<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia Sign Protocol on Crime Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- India and Russia on Wednesday
signed a protocol on combating organized crime, drug trafficking
and terrorism, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The nine-point protocol with three sub-clauses is a follow-up
of an earlier agreement reached between the two countries on
October 18, 1993.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed by visiting Russian Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister of Internal Affairs A. S. Kulikov and Indian Home
Minister Indrajit Gupta, provides for regular exchange of
information regarding organized criminal groups and their illegal
activities and connections with other criminal groups at the
global level.
</P>
<P>
Regular exchange of experts has been envisaged to facilitate
establishment of professional ties between the specialized police
training institutions of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The protocol also provides for coordinated action against
criminals and terrorist groups preceded by their identification.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters here soon after signing the protocol,
Kulikov and Gupta revealed that bilateral treaties on extradition
and mutual legal assistance in criminal matters have already been
finalized.
</P>
<P>
The new treaties are likely to be signed during Russian
President Boris Yeltsin's visit to India in January next year,
they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
