<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Reform Health Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government has
adopted a major reform program to ensure better health service in
the country in the next five years, a local newspaper reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
Major reform has been proposed in the Fifth Health and
Population Program to be implemented in the next five years with a
view to establishing an effective and efficient health and family
welfare services delivery system in the country, The Bangladesh
Times quoted Health and Family Welfare Minister Salahuddin Yusuf
as saying at a workshop on health service Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The present government is committed to ensuring basic minimum
health care for the entire population with particular emphasis on
the health of mothers, children and the poor, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,024 doctors have already been hired and 394 more
posts for doctors are being created for fresh recruitment, the
minister stated, adding that 4,000 more nurses are being
recruited.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government has set up a committee for formulating
the national health policy and a high-level committee for
reorganizing the health and family welfare sector, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minister said, the government will modify the
country's drug policy very soon.  
</P>
