<HEADLINE> Drought death toll Rises in Irian Jaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from drought in
eastern Indonesia has climbed to 445 people, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Malaria and cholera have been ravaging the people in Irian Jaya
Province as well as lack of food, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Seven people who died from cerebral malaria were the latest
victims in the isolated district of Jayawijaya in the central
mountain range of the province, the Kompas Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Severe malnutrition following crop failures and a lack of clean
water in the province since April has led to outbreaks of several
diseases such as diarrhea and malaria.
</P>
<P>
Of the victims, 398 were in Jayawijaya District, 23 in the
neighboring district of Merauke to the south and 24 in Puncakjaya
District to the west, Kompas said.
</P>
<P>
Jayawijaya District head J. B. Nenas said that so far a relief
operation has dropped 20 tons of rice to several drought-hit areas
as well as noodles, yam and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought has also triggered forest fires in
several islands, such as Sumatra, Kalimantan and Irian Jaya in the
country.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 1.7 million hectares of forest have been razed by
this year's forest fires, causing a health-threatening haze and an
estimated loss of 6.2 trillion rupiah (1.7 billion U.S. dollars),
according to the Indonesian Forum for Environment (WALHI). The
estimate was much higher than those given by government officials.
</P>
<P>
Some local experts predicted that the long-awaited monsoon rain
would come in November, but some ecologists forecast that the rain
would come in January.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
