<HEADLINE> Private Businesses Participate In State Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUJIAN, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Fujian Province, a model in
China's economic reform, has been taking its private sector into
account while renovating state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The eastern province has been guiding the successful merger of
some private businesses with state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The management of a state-owned tinned food producer, employing
more than 500 people in Xianyuo County, was entrusted to a private
Zhongmao Group Co. in 1993. The merged company, formerly in debt,
now turns out an annual pre-tax profit of 5 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The province's private businesses are expanding rapidly. The
added industrial value by the private sector constitutes 50
percent of the province's total added industrial value.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are 138 privately owned companies with sales from
50 to 100 million yuan each, and 60 firms with sales exceeding 100
million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
The province offers assistance to individually owned
enterprises undergoing reform in such areas as finances,
management, social security and property rights. 
