<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Oil Tankers Collide in Singapore Strait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Two oil tankers collided in
the Singapore Strait last night, resulting in an oil spill of
3,000 to 4,000 tons with no reports of injuries to crew members,
the Maritime Port Authority of Singapore (MPA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The collision occurred between an empty very large crude
carrier (VLCC) and an oil tanker in the Singapore Strait at about
9 p.m. last night, at a location just off the Singapore port
limits, where visibility then was about eight kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-registered VLCC "Orapin Global" of 129,702 gross tons
was transiting the Singapore Strait from east to west while the
Cyprus-flagged oil tanker "Evoikos," 75,428 gross tons, was
eastward-bound for Singapore from the United Arab Emirates. They
had been both warned of the impending collision by the Vessel
Traffic Information Service, the MPA said.
</P>
<P>
The MPA said the extent of damage to the Orapin Global, which
was empty at the time of the collision, has yet to be established.
But the damage to the Evoikos, which was carrying about 120,000
tons of marine fuel oil, is assessed to be two tanks, which caused
an oil spill of 3,000 to 4,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Both vessels are in no danger of sinking and there were no
reports of injuries to crew members, the MPA said, adding that
investigations are under way to identify the cause of the
collision and clean-up operations are being conducted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
