<HEADLINE> U.S. Optimistic About Serbs' Give-up of Heavy Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
optimistic that Bosnian Serbs will give up their heavy weapons and
comply more with the terms of an arms control agreement, a senior
U.S. administration official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The gap between what is expected of them and what they're
doing has reduced dramatically from the projections of a few
months ago," said the official, who spoke to a group of reporters
on condition of anonymity at the Foreign Press Club.
</P>
<P>
"Six months ago, the projections were a kind of alarming. It
looked as if the parties would be far out of line with the
ceilings, particularly the Bosnian Serbs," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dayton peace accord, the Muslim-Croat
federation can have 273 tanks and 1,000 artillery pieces while the
Serbs, who have some 1,000 tanks and cannons over the limit, was
allowed to have 137 tanks and 500 guns.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for the cut is November 1. The Bosnian Serbs
reportedly refused to part with their overwhelming advantage in
tanks and artillery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
