<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Calls for More ASEAN Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA (Malaysia), October 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad today stressed the need for the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to move toward
greater economic integration.
</P>
<P>
"To make ASEAN relevant in the next millennium we need to have
a longer term vision of what we want to be as an Association... We
need to set our sights higher... What is certain is that we need
to make the bold move toward greater economic integration, as we
will have to face an uncertain environment," he said when
officiating the 29th ASEAN Economic Ministers (AEM) meeting here.
</P>
<P>
He said that in moving toward greater economic integration,
ASEAN may need to look at the way the members cooperate with a new
perspective.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN must acknowledge that during the process, the members are
more exposed to the occurrence of disputes among themselves in
implementing the economic initiatives and have to resolve such
disputes swiftly and effectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While we implement initiatives toward greater economic
integration in ASEAN, we need to review regulatory and
administrative procedures at the national and ASEAN levels with a
view to making them more simple and transparent and ensure that
new measures introduced have the effect of facilitating decisions
and approvals," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir acknowledged that ASEAN will have to face enormous
challenges. "While standing together to face problems may not
amount to much, it is much safer than isolating ourselves in the
hope that we may not be noticed and thus left alone."
</P>
<P>
While ASEAN integrates economically, he said, the grouping
should also harness the benefits of information technology at a
very early stage before the enormity and speed of these
developments render it impossible for the region to catch up.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir spoke highly of ASEAN's "commendable achievements,"
which he said have made ASEAN an important player in international
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that for ASEAN's long-term prosperity, member
countries need to cooperate in macroeconomic policy formulation to
ensure the achievement of stable, sustainable economic growth for
the region.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, chaired by Malaysian International Trade
and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz, is being attended by trade and
economic ministers of the nine ASEAN countries -- Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand,
Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
