<HEADLINE> Myanmar Urges More Investment in Food Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government today
urged local and foreign entrepreneurs to make more investment in
the country's food production program and ensure food security.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony marking the World Food Day, Myint Aung, minister
for agriculture and irrigation, said the government is making
efforts to boost food production and ensure sufficiency for
domestic consumption and for export.
</P>
<P>
He said Myanmar, as a member of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN), is working closely with other nations in
the region in numerous areas including food production sectors
such as agriculture, livestock and fishery.
</P>
<P>
Today's official paper The New Light of Myanmar also said in
its commentary that the ministry has formed five working groups of
water supply, cultivation, agricultural education, finance and
supervision in the present fiscal year (1997-98) to help farmers
achieve the target of 20 million tons of rice production.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has been working to put 6.48 million hectares
under paddy yearly to realize the output target since the 1994-95
fiscal year, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The paper disclosed that the total output of Myanmar's
agricultural sector accounted for 36 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) and 35 percent of exports in fiscal 1996-97 with the
employment of 64 percent of the nation's labor force.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's total amount of exports of more than 883.3
million U.S. dollars, nearly 313.3 million were from the sector,
it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the country's main economic sector with rice,
beans and pulses, cotton and sugarcane as its chief export items.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's rice production in
the 1996-97 fiscal year was 17.08 million tons with 93,100 tons
exported.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics also show that Myanmar's rice export in
the first six months of 1997 reached merely 1,200 tons, down from
241,700 tons in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's GDP grew by 5.8 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year,
in which agricultural production increased by 3.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
