<HEADLINE> Thailand to See Only 1.6-Percent Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic growth for
fiscal 1998 could reach only 1.6 percent following massive cuts in
the budget for fiscal 1998, according to a Budget Bureau source
today.
</P>
<P>
For fiscal 1997, which ended on September 30, the bureau
expects the country's gross domestic product (GDP) to grow by 2.1
percent, compared with about 6.8 percent for 1996.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's forecasts contrast with those announced by Deputy
Prime Minister Virabongsa Ramangkura on Tuesday, when he said the
country's economic growth for 1997 would be 2.5 percent and 3.5
percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday the cabinet approved cuts of 100 billion baht (2.75
billion U.S. dollars) in the fiscal 1998 budget, reducing it to
823 billion baht (22.64 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The cuts were made as required by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to achieve a budget surplus of 1 percent of GDP in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit will improve from 5.6 percent of
GDP this year to 2.6 percent in 1998, the source quoted Budget
Bureau Director-General Seri Suksathaporn as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
