<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Become World's Top Auto Producer and Consumer by 2015 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Asia will replace North America as
the world's largest motor vehicle manufacturing area by year 2015,
while its market share will be the same as the combined amount of the
United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the on-going 15th World Petroleum Congress, Tsutomu
Kagawa, managing director of the Japan Automobile Manufacturers
Association, said here today that Asia is expected to account for
36 percent of the world output of four-wheeled vehicles by 2015,
compared with North America and Western Europe at 25 percent and
19 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to Kagawa, production output worldwide is projected
at 92.3 million in 2015, with corresponding sales figures being
just about the same. In the past two decades, production of motor
vehicles has grown by about 18 million.
</P>
<P>
In sales, Asia is expected to grow rapidly, especially from the
year 2000. By 2015, it should account for 36 percent of worldwide
sales also, again surpassing North America and Western Europe by a
wide margin.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, similar trends are seen in the increase of the market
share or ownership of four-wheeled vehicles worldwide. Asia is to
gain 28 percent of the market in 18 years' time from 19 percent in
1995. In the meantime, North America and Western Europe, currently
largest and second largest consumers, will register steady
decline, from 1995's 35 percent and 29 percent to 2015's 28
percent and 22 percent of the market scale respectively.
</P>
<P>
The shares of Eastern Europe and other regional markets are
also expected to grow, but at a slower pace, said Kagawa.
</P>
<P>
Because of the growth of the population of motor vehicles, fuel
consumption worldwide is expected to grow by 1.6 folds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
