<HEADLINE> Economist: IMF to Ask Indonesia to Reform Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will likely require Indonesia to reform its banking sector
and trade regime and revise its state budget as part of a scheme
to restore confidence in the country's economy, a noted economist
said.
</P>
<P>
"Standard IMF reforms to restore a country's economy are
banking sector, trade and state budget," Mari Pangestu, managing
director of the Center for Strategic and International Studies,
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will need at least two years to recover from the
current economic crisis, even with IMF help, Pangestu was quoted
as saying by the local press today.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government decided last week to seek
international assistance in face of continued weakening of the
rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian officials and IMF team members began closed-door
meeting on Monday to work out reform policies and possible loans.
</P>
<P>
Pangestu has joined those who say Indonesia will likely obtain
funds of some 12 billion U.S. dollars from the IMF, in the form of
stand-by loans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian rupiah, the national currency, fell
past 3,500 against the dollar in late trading Wednesday on
continued local dollar demand.
</P>
<P>
"Domestic dollar buying interest seems to continue. Sporadic
intervention by the central bank at the 3,500 and 3,560 levels had
not helped," a U.S. dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah dropped to a low of 3,595 in the afternoon before
profit-taking and the central bank emerged, sending the dollar
back to 3,560/80.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index
went down by 1.9 percent to 518.19 points on closing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary Moerdiono said Tuesday that an IMF mission here
was discussing "technical assistance" for Indonesia's efforts to
overcome the crisis that followed the fall of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
However, reports have said the IMF was preparing an aid package
that would include billions of dollars in loans.
</P>
<P>
Government officials here said earlier that the value of the
rupiah has dropped by 46 percent against the dollar since the
beginning of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
