<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Opens Economic Ministers Meeting in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA (Malaysia), October 16 (Xinhua) -- The 29th ASEAN
Economic Ministers (AEM) meeting opened here today at a time when
most ASEAN economies are tested due to the speculative attacks on
their currencies.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was inaugurated by Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and is attended by Laos and Myanmar, both
admitted into ASEAN last July, for the first time, and by all the
other members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Cambodia is present as an
observer.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to mainly focus on the currency and
stock market turmoil that has swept the region as host Malaysia's
proposal to study the impact of the currency attack on regional
economies is included in the agenda for the AEM.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil affected Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand and the
Philippines most, and to a lesser extent Singapore, with the
currencies of the first four having depreciated by between 25-35
percent against the U.S. dollar since July.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia wants the inputs to assess the impact of currency
changes on trade within and outside ASEAN to complement efforts by
the International Monetary Fund and World Bank to rethink the
effects speculative currency trading is having on domestic and
regional economies.
</P>
<P>
Expected to be reviewed at the meeting are the ASEAN Free Trade
Area (AFTA) where tariffs would be between only zero and 5 percent
by the year 2003, the ASEAN Industrial Cooperation scheme, the
framework for the proposed ASEAN Investment Area which seeks to
reduce barriers to the free flow of capital and the adoption of
similar and more transparent rules to complement the AFTA scheme.
</P>
<P>
Other issues the ministers would likely deliberate on include
the soon to be endorsed Trade and Customs Tariff Notification
Procedure which requires member countries to inform each other of
any modifications in the AFTA commitments and obligations which
might impair or nullify any benefit to members.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, AEM dialogues would be held with the Closer
Economic Relations countries of Australia and New Zealand, the
Southern African Development Community and Japan's Ministry of
International Trade and Industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
