<HEADLINE> Three European States End Talks With China on Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Hungary, the Czech Republic and
Slovakia have ended bilateral talks with China on mutual market
access under the World Trade Organization (WTO), China's deputy
trade minister Long Yongtu announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Hungary signed the agreement of mutual market access with China
in July, becoming the first European country to make such a deal
with China during the negotiations on China's accession to the
WTO. The two sides agreed that the deal be made public today.
</P>
<P>
Long met with Hungary's representative to the WTO, Ambassador
Istvan Major, here today to extend thanks to Hungary for its
contribution to the ongoing process of China's WTO accession.
</P>
<P>
Major told Long that the Hungarian government holds that the
WTO needs China and the relationship between the WTO and China are
mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
Although the talks on China's accession to the WTO are somewhat
difficult, Major pointed out, their ultimate smooth conclusion
will make a significant impact on the formation of world trade and
the existing multilateral trade system itself.
</P>
<P>
Long and his delegation have been in Geneva for a series of
talks since October 5. Earlier this week, he signed agreements
respectively with representatives of the Czech Republic and
Slovakia, ending bilateral talks on market access.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in Geneva, the Chinese delegation also had
bilateral talks with more than 20 developing countries like
Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, India and Indonesia, and some developed
countries like Norway. Most of the countries have been close to
the conclusion of the negotiations over market access with China,
Long said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
