<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD, Asia to Rely More on Oil Imports: IEA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) countries and the Asian region
will witness a significant rise in dependence on oil imports in
the coming decade, the International Energy Agency (IEA) said
today.
</P>
<P>
The OECD's dependence on oil imports will not change remarkably
by the year 2000, but will rise considerably over the following
decade, IEA executive director Robert Priddle said at the 15th
World Petroleum Congress here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The OECD will rely on imports to meet around 60 percent of its
total oil demand by 2010, compared to about 50 percent at present,
Priddle said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, since oil production in the developing Asian region is
expected to be sluggish, high oil demand growth there indicates a
sharp increase in their import requirements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian countries currently import around 40 percent of their
oil consumption and the figure is expected to jump to 65 percent
in 2010, Priddle predicted.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of oil imports will come from the Middle East and world
oil supplies will become increasingly reliant on OPEC countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The significant required inflow of oil to Asia from the Middle
East will be a key aspect of world trade patterns and changing
energy security considerations," Priddle said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
