<HEADLINE> Thailand Hikes Customs Duties to Encourage Automakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The increase of customs duties
on completely-built cars to 80 percent from 42 percent and 68.5
percent will encourage automakers to start assembling more cars
locally, the Automobile Industry Club of the Federation of Thai
industries said.
</P>
<P>
The new duty rate on cars is part of a wide-ranging series of
tax increases included in the government financial reform package
announced on Tuesday. The increases all took effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
Surapong Paisitpatnapong, a spokesman for the club, was quoted
today by the local press as saying Japanese car companies would
have to think about stepping up production in Thailand, given the
higher tax and the weaker baht.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that it would be tougher to sell imported cars in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Car imports in the past eight months have fallen to 14,038
units, a 45-percent drop from the same period of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
