<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Flying Tigers" Return To Battlefield In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Forty-six surviving members of
the Flying Tigers Association were in Kunming, capital of China's
Yunnan province this week, more than fifty years after having
fought the Japanese there in World War Two.
</P>
<P>
The men, most of whom are in their late seventies and eighties,
were accompanied by family members. They climbed a hill in the
western suburbs of Kunming to mourn their war dead at a monument
in their honor.
</P>
<P>
The American volunteers set up a 282-man base in 1941 in
Kunming, and shot down 6 out of 10 attacking Japanese aircraft in
the skies over Yunnan on December 20, 1941, and crippled the other
4.
</P>
<P>
The first victory caused them to be known as the "Flying
Tigers", and they became war heroes who have long been remembered
by the Chinese people. The people of Kunming rushed into the
streets to celebrate the victory.
</P>
<P>
Historians say the Flying Tigers played a very important role
in the Allied effort in the Second World War, and were taking on
the supposedly invincible Japanese Air Force, a much stronger
force.
</P>
<P>
Some 56 years later, the local people decorated the streets
with flowers to pay their respect to these war heroes, who had
fought to protect the city. Robert F. Layher, who shot down five
Japanese aircraft, told Xinhua that he continued to think of the
friendly people of Kunming, after having left China for so many
years.
</P>
<P>
He was 24 years old when he left China, but says that Kunming
is becoming younger and more charming 56 years later, although he
has gotten old.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was very impressive to see many high buildings
near the site of the military airport of 56 year ago, where there
used to be bombed-out houses.
</P>
<P>
The visitors will also make a trip to Guilin and to Chongqing,
and tour the Command Office of the U.S. 14th Air Fleet in the
1940s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean President Inspects Earthquake-Shaken Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Eduardo Frei
left here today for the Forth Region in the northern part of the
country, after a strong earthquake hit the region Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measuring at 6.8 on the Richter scale, was recorded
in northern and central Chile at 22:03 local time (0203 GMT
Wednesday), leaving eight people dead and 55 injured.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Public Works Ricardo Lagos today described as
normal and under control the situation in the north, the most
affected area in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The National Emergency Agency said that the tremor caused
damage in some houses and public buildings, leaving power cut and
telephone lines broke down.
</P>
<P>
A bridge on the Pisco Elqui-Rio Hurtado freeway was also torn
down, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Police Director General Fernando Cordero Rusque
also asserted that the situation in the most affected areas is
under control, while there are possible risks in delivering aid to
some small towns.
</P>
<P>
Cordero said the Police has sent helicopters to the afflicted
areas.
</P>
<P>
An air force plane, loaded with humanitarian aid from the
National Emergency Office, took off this afternoon and flew to the
city of La Serena, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian cargo includes 600 blankets, 580 boxes of food
and 300 mattresses.
</P>
<P>
Besides, two more planes will be sent to deliver supplies and
foodstuff to some remote towns in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Jaime Mondaca, manager of the state-owned
railroad company, said today that the quake caused no damage to
the railroads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
