<HEADLINE> Western Petroleum Capital Floods into Central Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Western multinational
corporations have begun to channel their capital into Central
Asian countries, mainly in local energy industries.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, and Turkmenistan -- rich in
oil and natural gas resources -- are especially attractive to
Western investors because of growing political stability in the
newly independent nations, according to delegates from those
countries attending the 15th World Petroleum Congress.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan is a potential oil producer along the Caspian
Sea. Six Japanese and Turkish companies have signed contracts with
the country to spend 500 million U.S. dollars during 1996-1999 on
oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
A Malaysian oil company also signed an agreement to develop
Turkmenistan's three oilfields along the Caspian Sea continental
shelf. And a British company has invested 300 million US dollars
in the development of three oilfields in the west.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 foreign companies also are involved in the oil and
natural gas field of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Uzbekistan has received more than a billion U.S. dollars in
direct foreign investment for processing and tapping energy
resources.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Kyrgyzstan also has been focused on
petroleum and natural gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
