<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Ends Brazil Visit Without Progress in FTAA Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton ended his visit to Brazil today without making significant
progress in the process of setting up the Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA) even though he managed to reach several accords.
</P>
<P>
Clinton left here for Buenos Aires, capital of Argentina, the
last leg of a week-long trip that also took him to Venezuela and
Brazil. He will return to Washington on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During Clinton's two-day visit to Brazil, the two countries
signed seven cooperation agreements on education, space,
environment, peaceful use of nuclear energy, the fight against
drug trafficking and the extradition process.
</P>
<P>
But he left unsolved some issues, such as the FTAA and the
U.S. commercial barriers against 100 Brazilian products.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference, Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso said his country needs time to prepare its
entrance to FTAA, a hemispheric trade bloc proposed for 2005.
</P>
<P>
Brazil fears that the creation of a free trade zone would wreck
its industrial sector, already shaken by a first round of tariff
reductions earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said the United States is willing to support
the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) which consists of Brazil,
Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
Clinton insisted that Mercosur should not be in contradiction
with the setting up of FTAA.
</P>
<P>
However, the two presidents said they agreed to talk about the
issue in March 1998 in Santiago, Chile, at the 2nd summit of the
Americas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
