<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Oil Demand to Grow 30 Percent by 2010: IEA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 16 (Xinhua) -- World oil demand is expected to
grow by about 30 percent in the 15 years to 2010, the
International Energy Agency (IEA) predicted here today.
</P>
<P>
Oil demand will total between 92 and 97 million barrels a day
in the year 2010, compared to 72 million barrels a day in 1996,
Robert Priddle, executive director of the agency, told the 15th
World Petroleum Congress (WPC) this morning.
</P>
<P>
"The locus of world oil demand growth will be in the non-OECD
countries, with growth rates double those of the OECD," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, he noted, the OECD countries will account for
only 50 percent of world oil demand, down from 57 percent at
present.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the demand growth will be mainly driven by the
strong economies of the Asian region, Priddle said, adding that
Asian demand will have doubled from its 1995 level of 11 million
barrels a day to at least 22 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
Asian demand will account for over 40 percent of the total
increase in world demand during the same period, with east Asia
expected to take a 25 percent share in world demand growth, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that "China alone will account for 13 percent
of global demand growth during the period."
</P>
<P>
"As the major part of energy demand increase will occur outside
the OECD region, the future pattern of energy demand in the
non-OECD countries will be a determining factor of long-term
global energy demand," Priddle said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0324 </DOCNO>
