<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak President, PM Vow to Eradicate Poverty, Hunger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif today reaffirmed their
country's commitment to eradicate poverty, hunger and
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
In their messages on the occasion of World Food Day, which is
observed today, Leghari and Sharif stressed it has been Pakistan's
continuing effort to attain food self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
"This day provides an opportunity to highlight the importance
of food and agriculture and to focus on the vital issue of food
security which is of paramount concern to the entire world," said
Leghari in his message.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Pakistan is essentially an agricultural country
with about two-thirds of its population directly or indirectly
connected with this sector.
</P>
<P>
It has been Pakistan's continuing effort to attain
self-sufficiency in food and also to provide agricultural
surpluses for the world to cater to the ever-rising demand, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Congratulating the Food and Agriculture Organization of the
United Nations on the 52nd anniversary of its founding, Sharif
said in his message that the selection of the theme "Investing in
Food Security" for this occasion is very appropriate.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that the government of Pakistan has launched an
"Agricultural Incentive Package" with a view to boosting
agricultural produce by providing various incentives to encourage
both public and private sector investments.
</P>
<P>
As a short-term measure, he said, "we have declared year 1998
as Wheat Year to improve wheat production."
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that these steps will go a long way in providing
food security, on a sustained basis, not only to cater for our
domestic needs but also for the world food grains pool," he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the Food and Agriculture Organization as an active
partner in Pakistan's endeavors to improve both production and
productivity in the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that this partnership would continue to our
mutual benefit and will help in resolving the prevalent problem of
hunger and malnutrition in the Third World countries," the prime
minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
