<HEADLINE> Maradona Against New Anti-doping Law in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 15 (Xinhua) -- World soccer superstar
Diego Maradona claimed on Tuesday here that he would lead a
football players' strike against the new law brought in by the
Argentinian parliament for positive drugs tests.
</P>
<P>
The law led to a two-year suspension for Albeiro Usuriaga of
Colombia for Cocaine abuse. Usuriaga tested positive after a match
on August 24.
</P>
<P>
Maradoa, who is under threat of getting the same penalty as
Usuriaga, said he was shocked by the punishment of the Colombian.
</P>
<P>
Another player Diego Latorre said in a television discussion
that the players should get together to discuss the ramifications
of the law and if it was felt necessary then they should strike.
</P>
<P>
Maradona could also face a term in prison after Argentina's
Appeal Court turned down his appeal in September challenging a
four-year prison sentence imposed by a provincial court after
shooting incident,
</P>
<P>
Maradona's offer to do "community service" instead of serve a
prison sentence, was rejected. 
</P>
