<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Price Index Rises in NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Consumer Price Index
(CPI) rose 0.5 percent in New Zealand in the third quarter this
year, Statistics NZ announced in a media release received today.
</P>
<P>
The rate is higher than expected, but in line with Reverse Bank
forecasts. It brings the annual inflation rate for the year ending
September 30 to 1 percent, the lowest yearly rise for the past
four and half years.
</P>
<P>
Contributing to most of the quarterly rise were higher housing
costs, which went up 1.4 percent in the quarter. Dearer tobacco
and alcohol were also blamed for the CPI rise.
</P>
<P>
But lower mortgage costs, which fell 1.7 percent in the three
months, partly offset the rise, Statistics NZ said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the figures, economists predicted that interest
rates and the NZ dollar might continue to ease in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
But they cautioned that money borrowers should not expect a big
drop in lending rates after the announcement of the inflation
figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales Decline in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Total sales of vehicles in the
Philippines dropped 2.86 percent in the first nine months of the
year due to soaring interest rates and depreciation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales from January to September of the year fell to
116,490 units from 119,992 in the same period of last year, latest
data released by the Chamber of Automotive Manufacturers showed.
</P>
<P>
Sales of passenger cars went down 7.2 percent while commercial
vehicle sales fell 2.4 percent, according to the data.
</P>
<P>
The high cost of borrowing money in the country and the weak
peso jacked up production costs and made the cost of leasing a
motor vehicle prohibitive, it said.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry's biggest loser was Toyota Motor Philippines
Corp., which suffered a 16.5-percent sales drop to 25,408 units
from 30,427 units it sold in the first nine months of 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
