<HEADLINE> Pak Confirms Benazir's Swiss Bank Accounts Blocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss authorities have
blocked accounts worth 13.7 million U.S. dollars belonging to
former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and her family
members, a senior official confirmed here today.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss authorities also froze the accounts of "at least six
other companies of Benazir and her husband, Asif Ali Zardari,"
said Saif-ur-Rehman, chairman of Ehtesab (anti-corruption) Cell of
the Prime Minister Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
"The blockade has been the result of the efforts of the Ehtesab
Cell team which has worked day and night for 15 days in
Switzerland and provided the authorities there with solid proofs
that they siphoned off money from Pakistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the cell has further documentary evidence against
Bhutto and her family members that "they transferred the money to
foreign banks through illegal means."
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, reports from Geneva, Switzerland, said the Swiss
authorities had blocked bank accounts belonging to Benazir and her
relatives containing around 20 million Swiss francs (about 13.7
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted a spokesman for the Bern Police Ministry,
Folco Galli, as saying that "there is a possibility that other
Bhutto accounts would be frozen."
</P>
<P>
"It depends on whether we get more information from Pakistan.
It's not excluded we'll freeze more money," the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
