<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Factor in Brain Development Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A unique interaction between
proteins produced by two genes is believed to play a key role in
normal brain development, according to a team of U.S. scientists.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the genes, called mdab1 and reelin, may help
in the search for cancer cures and more effective treatments for
brain disorders, said scientists at the Tennessee-based St. Jude
Children's Research Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Their findings are carried by the Nature magazine in its latest
issue, the hospital reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the findings, mdab1 is in brain cells while reelin
acts as a guidepost outside brain cells. Their interaction results
in a signal relay activated insided cells, allowing intercellular
communication or brain development to proceed.
</P>
<P>
For the brain to develop normally, newly generated neurons in
the cerebral cortex must migrate outward, past layers of
preexisting cells. When this process is disrupted, the brain fails
to become fully organized, the scientists believed.
</P>
<P>
The report suggests that mutations in one of both of the mdab1
and reelin genes are at least partially responsible for the
devastating effects arising from abnormal brain development.
</P>
<P>
Brain disorders like schizophrenia and childhood epilepsy are
possibly caused by mutations of these genes.
</P>
<P>
The scientists said their findings are based on biochemical
studies of mice which have identical phenotypes and mutations in
these genes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971016.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Budgets 26.6 Billion US Dollars in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Intelligence
Agency (CIA) of the United States disclosed today that it budgeted
26.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, the first time for the agency
to declassify its spending on spy in its 50-year operation.
</P>
<P>
"The aggregate amount appropriated for intelligence and
intelligence-related activities for fiscal year 1997 is 26.6
billion dollars," CIA Director George Tenet said in response to a
Freedom of Information lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
About 10 billion dollars of the total goes for tactical
military intelligence, serving battlefield commanders; about 3
billion dollars spends on the CIA itself; the National Security
Agency, which conducts electronic eavesdropping and decoding
operations, gets about 4 billion dollars; the National
Reconnaissance Office, which builds and operates spy satellites,
gets about 6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rest is divided among a variety of intelligence analysis
agencies such as the National Imagery and Mapping Agency, and
intelligence offices at the FBI, the State Department, the Energy
Department and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The spending is smaller than the 34.5 billion dollars in 1989
and is about the average for the last decade of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Tenet also said the administration would decide on a
year-by-year basis whether to reveal overall intelligence
spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
