<HEADLINE> New York Share Prices Slip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street fell
modestly today as investors were disappointed by the profit report
of Intel and worried about signs of heavy consumer demand that
could spur inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 38.31 points to 8,057.98.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 504.68 million
shares as against 510.35 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also slipped as interest rates rose in
the bond market after a stronger-than-expected reading on
September's retail sales fueled fears the Federal Reserve may slow
the economy to protect against inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 4.55 to 965.73, the
NYSE composite index fell 1.68 to 506.89, and the Nasdaq composite
index fell 9.73 to 1,723.06
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.23 to 462.74,
the second straight drop for that high-flying measure. The American
Stock Exchange composite index, which is dominated by smaller
companies, fell 0.45 to 714.34.
</P>
<P>
Before today's open, the U.S. Commerce Department reported that
retail sales rose 0.3 percent in September, the fourth consecutive
monthly increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
