<HEADLINE> Greek Police to Step Up Efforts to Combat Drunk Driving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Greek traffic police will step
up efforts to reduce alcohol-related road accidents by extending
breathalyser testing for drunk driving to toll posts along the
national highways throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Public Order Minister George Romeos said today that with the
setting up of 21 new breathalyser devices donated by the
Association of Insurance Companies at toll stations, Greek traffic
police now have a total of 101 breathalyser kits, enabling alcohol
testing across the country.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents in the wider Athens region have reportedly
reduced by 25-27 percent since breathalyser testing was introduced
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
George Skourtis, a spokesman for the association and chairman
of its accidents committee, said that if road accidents continued
to decline at the present rate, the next step would be a reduction
in car insurance premiums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
