<HEADLINE> US Opposes Angola Involving in Congo's Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
opposed Angola for its involvement in the civil war in the Congo
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"The point is that we do not support their involvement there,
that they don't belong there," State Department spokesman James
Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Rubin's remarks referred to the help given by Angolan troops to
former Congo military leader Denis Sassou Nguesso in his fight,
which started in June, against President Pascal Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Sassou proclaimed victory in the battle for the
capital Brazzaville and the capture of the key southern oil town
Pointe Noire with the help of the Angolan forces.
</P>
<P>
Pointe Noire, the Congo's oil and economic capital, is the seat
of the Congolese high command and Lissouba's main logistical
supply point.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said, "We have made clear to the Angolans in this context
that we expect them to help safeguard U.S. lives in Pointe Noire."
</P>
</TEXT>
