<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Accused of Aggravating Regional Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Greek Defense Minister
Akis Tsohatzopoulos today accused Turkey of aggravating regional
tensions, and defended Greek-Cypriot defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference together with his Cypriot
counterpart Costas Eliades, Tsohatzopoulos urged the international
community to pressurize Turkey to withdraw its troops from Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister, who was here to review a Cypriot military
exercise jointly participated by Greek naval and air forces,
contended that the Greek-Cypriot defense agreement had not led to
any tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed in 1993 a defense pact, under which
Greece would provide Cyprus with military assistance in case the
island was attacked.
</P>
<P>
He said that Greece and Cyprus would again launch joint
military exercises next year.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over a number of issues
concerning the Aegean Sea as well as Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' defense minister told reporters that the defense
cooperation between Cyprus and Greece was irreversible, unless the
demilitarization of the island was agreed upon or the Cyprus
problem was resolved.
</P>
<P>
Eliades said that Cyprus was ready and determined to face any
situation or threat posed by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops seized
the northern third following an abortive pro-Athens coup by Greek
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, which was
declared by Turkish Cypriots in 1983 as the "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
