<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Suggests Future Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LEIPZIG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
today surprisingly made clear that he wants his party's
parliamentary group leader, Wolfgang Schaeuble, to be his future
successor.
</P>
<P>
"It is known to everybody that I hope Schaeuble would once
become chancellor," Kohl said in an television interview at the
end of a three-day congress of his Christian Democratic Union
(CDU) party.
</P>
<P>
But he was also careful not to specify when this should happen.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who has been German chancellor since 1982, has already
decided to seek an unprecedented fifth term by runing for the next
general elections due in September next year.
</P>
<P>
Schaeuble, 55, has been regarded as Kohl's closest ally and a
strategist behind the chancellor. He has been confined to a
wheelchair since being attacked by a mentally disturbed man at a
1990 election rally.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts suggested that by announcing Schaeuble as his
future successor, Kohl might not prepare to serve a full four-year
term if being re-elected next year.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to Kohl's remarks, the main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) said that Schaeuble did not need to nourish
any hope for the chancellor post because Kohl's party would be
defeated next year.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll published today by the Frankfurt Allgemeine
newspaper also showed that Kohl's party continued to trail the SPD
in support rates.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, however, said earlier that it was not polls but election
results that counted.
</P>
<P>
Closing the CDU congress in the eastern German city of Leipzig
today, Kohl declared that his party had "an excellent chance" to
win the next elections.
</P>
<P>
"We will fight for every vote. We have made it clear that we
will fight for victory," he told the cheering delegates.
</P>
<P>
The three-day CDU congress has confirmed Kohl's leadership as
well as his candidacy for next year's elections. An election
platform was also adopted today with focus on cutting unemployment
and fighting crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
