<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Acknowledges Difficulties of Doha Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
acknowledged difficulties to make the fourth Middle East economic
summit a real summit because of the deadlocked Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"We do recognize reality. And the reality is that in the
absence of continued improvements in the Middle East peace
process, it will be difficult to get the best possible summit,"
State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The fourth Middle East economic summit, scheduled for November
16-18 in Doha, the Qatar capital, was intended by the United
States to pull Arab nations and Israel together to strengthen
their economic relations.
</P>
<P>
But some Arab nations made it clear during U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright's visit to the region that whether and at
what level they would attend the conference would be determined by
progress in U.S.-sponsored Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which
went aground in March when Israel started construction of Jewish
housing units in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told reporters that a conference steering committee met
Tuesday in Washington to discuss preparations for the summit, with
delegations from Qatar, Egypt, Tunisia, Russia, Jordan, Morocco,
Israel, Canada, the European Union and Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Representatives affirmed participation in the event and
discussed logistical preparations. It was a productive meeting,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
But he said he did not think all countries had yet decided at
what level they would be represented, although some foreign
ministers were expected. Albright also plans to attend.
</P>
<P>
He believed Saudi Arabia, which has been critical of the
summit, would have "some kind" of representation there.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East mediator Dennis Ross has been shuttling
between Israel and Arab nations in recent days in an effort to
revive peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians, and he
will leave for the region again at the weekend to continue his
difficult mission.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said he hoped Ross's effort and Albright's Middle East
trip could improve the situation there and thus "improve the
representation (at Doha) and therefore improve the success of the
conference." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
